{"title_page": "Ken Liu", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| name        = Ken Liu\n| image       = Ken Liu 2016.jpg\n| caption     = Liu at the 2016 Texas Book Festival\n| birth_name  = {{zh|c=\u5218\u5b87\u6606|p=Li\u00fa Y\u01d4k\u016bn|labels=no}}\n| birth_date  = 1976\n| birth_place = [[Lanzhou]], China\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = Author, translator, lawyer, programmer\n| nationality = American\n| period      = \n| genre       = [[Science fiction]], [[fantasy]]\n| subject     = \n| movement    = \n| notableworks= {{Plainlist}}\n* ''[[The Paper Menagerie]]'' (2011)\n* ''The Grace of Kings'' (2015)\n* ''[[The Three-Body Problem (novel)|The Three-Body Problem]]'' (2015 {{abbr|transl.|translation into English}})\n* \"[[Byzantine Empathy]]\" (2018 short)\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| spouse      = Lisa Tang Liu<ref name=strangehorizons />\n| children    = \n| relatives   = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| awards      = {{Plainlist}}\n* [[Hugo Award]]s (\u00d73)\n* [[Locus Award]]s (\u00d72)\n* [[FantLab's Book of the Year Award|FantLab's Award]]s (\u00d72)\n* [[Nebula Award]] (\u00d71)\n* [[Sidewise Award for Alternate History|Sidewise Award]] (\u00d71)\n* [[World Fantasy Award]] (\u00d71)\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| signature   = \n| website     = {{Official URL}}\n| portaldisp  = \n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese|t=\u5289\u5b87\u6606|s=\u5218\u5b87\u6606|p=Li\u00fa Y\u01d4k\u016bn}}\n\n'''Ken Liu''' (born 1976) is an award-winning [[Americans|American]] author of [[science-fiction]] and [[fantasy]], as well as a translator, lawyer, and computer programmer.  His epic fantasy series ''The Dandelion Dynasty'', the first work in the \"silkpunk\" genre, is published by [[Simon & Schuster]].<ref name=\"tordotcomsummary\">{{cite web |title=Ken Liu Talks Silkpunk, Old Poems, and Contemporary Chinese SFF in His Reddit AMA |url=https://www.tor.com/2015/04/13/ken-liu-reddit-ama-highlights/ |website=Tor.com}}</ref> His short stories have appeared in ''[[F&SF]]'', ''[[Asimov's]]'', ''[[Analog Science Fiction and Fact|Analog]]'', ''[[Lightspeed (magazine)|Lightspeed]]'', ''[[Clarkesworld]]'', and multiple \"Year's Best\" anthologies.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Clarkesworld Magazine - Science Fiction & Fantasy|url = http://clarkesworldmagazine.com/awards_and_recognition/|website = Clarkesworld Magazine|accessdate = 2015-10-11|language = en}}</ref>\n\n==Childhood and career==\nLiu was born in 1976 in [[Lanzhou]], [[China]].<ref name=\"nw103016\"/> He spent his childhood with his grandparents.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ken Liu Talks Silkpunk, Old Poems, and Contemporary Chinese SFF in His Reddit AMA |url=https://www.tor.com/2015/04/13/ken-liu-reddit-ama-highlights/ |website=Tor.com |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref> His mother, who received her Ph.D. in Chemistry in the United States, is a pharmaceutical chemist, while his father is a computer engineer.<ref name=\"asiaone\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.asiaone.com/ken-liu-won-science-fiction-awards-best-short-story?nopaging=1\n|title=Ken Liu won science fiction awards for best short story\n|accessdate=2019-01-05\n|date=2013-09-09\n|publisher=[[AsiaOne]]\n}}</ref> The family emigrated to the United States when Liu was 11 years old.<ref name=\"nw103016\">{{cite web\n|url=https://www.newsweek.com/man-bringing-chinese-science-fiction-west-514893\n|title=MEET THE MAN BRINGING CHINESE SCIENCE FICTION TO THE WEST\n|accessdate=2019-01-05\n|date=2016-10-30\n|publisher=[[Newsweek]]\n}}</ref> They lived in [[California]] and [[Stonington, Connecticut|Stonington]] before settling in [[Waterford, Connecticut|Waterford]]. Liu graduated from [[Waterford High School (Connecticut)|Waterford High School]] in 1994, where he ran cross-country and track.<ref name=\"day\">{{cite web\n|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20150414/ENT02/150419746\n|title=Waterford alum \u2014 and award-winning short story writer \u2014 Ken Liu releases his debut novel\n|accessdate=2019-01-05\n|date=2015-04-14\n|publisher=[[The Day (New London)]]\n}}</ref> At [[Harvard College]], he studied English Literature and Computer Science, receiving his A. B. in 1998.<ref name=\"day\"/><ref name=hm>{{cite web\n|url=https://harvardmagazine.com/2016/11/fusion-fantasy\n|title=Fusion Fantasy:Ken Liu's sprawling hybrid fiction\n|accessdate=2019-01-05\n|date=November\u2013December 2016\n|publisher=[[Harvard Magazine]]\n}}</ref> After graduation, he worked as a software engineer for [[Microsoft]], and then joined a start-up in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]. He later received his J.D. from [[Harvard Law School]] in 2004 and after working as a corporate lawyer, eventually became a high-tech litigation consultant.<ref name=\"day\"/><ref name=hm/> He began publishing fiction in 2002. His first published work was \"Carthaginian Rose\", a short story on [[mind uploading]] which was published alongside nine other authors in [[The Phobos Science Fiction Anthology Volume 1]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Ken |title=Carthaginian Rose |url=https://kenliu.name/stories/carthaginian-rose/ |website=Ken Liu, Writer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214061409/https://kenliu.name/stories/carthaginian-rose/ |archive-date=14 December 2019 |accessdate=14 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter a long career writing and publishing short fiction, Liu turned to epic fantasy novels, starting with ''The Grace of Kings'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Interview: Ken Liu |url=http://www.lightspeedmagazine.com/nonfiction/interview-ken-liu/ |website=Lightspeed |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref> He has also written for the [[Star Wars]] universe, with ''The Legends of Luke Skywalker'' in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=Interview on The Legends of Luke Skywalker |url=https://www.starwars.com/news/ken-liu-exploring-perfect-mythic-figure-the-legends-of-luke-skywalker |website=StarWars.com |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlong with his original work, Ken Liu has found work in translating. He has translated the works of multiple Chinese authors into English, including [[w: Liu Cixin| Liu Cixin]], [[w:Hao Jingfang|Hao Jingfang]], [[w: Chen Qiufan| Chen Qiufan]], [[w:Xia Jia| Xia Jia]], and others.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chinese SF and the art of translation |url=http://blogs.nature.com/futureconditional/2016/08/20/chinese-sf-and-the-art-of-translation-a-qa-with-ken-liu/ |website=Nature.com |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>. His translation of ''[[w: The Three-Body Problem (novel)|The Three Body Problem]]'' by Liu Cixin helped the book become a best seller to English readers.<ref>{{cite web |title=How Ken Liu went from engineer to lawyer to SF writer to the foremost translator of Chinese sf into English| url=https://boingboing.net/2019/12/04/rod-serling-w-chinese-characte.html |website= boingboing.net |accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> He also has worked on editing works. While editing the anthology ''Invisible Planets'', Ken Liu translated the stories contained within it from Chinese into English. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://electricliterature.com/ken-liu-will-keep-an-open-mind/|title=Ken Liu Will Keep an Open Mind|website=electricliterature.com|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome of Liu's work have been adapted into visual media. \"Memories of My Mother,\" a short story, was the basis of \"Beautiful Dreamer\" by David Gaddie.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4794788/ |website=IMDB |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref> \"Real Artists,\" a short story, was adapted into a short film by Cameo Wood.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5648094/ |website=IMDB}}</ref> \"Good Hunting,\" a short story, was adapted into an animated short as part of [[Netflix]]'s ''[[Love, Death & Robots]]'' series in 2019.\n\n==Awards==\n\nLiu's short story \"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\" is the first work of fiction, of any length, to win the Nebula, Hugo, and World Fantasy Awards.<ref name=\"strangehorizons\">{{cite web |url=http://www.strangehorizons.com/2013/20130325/1reid-a.shtml |title=Not Just Vast Armies Clashing on Dark Plains at Night: An Interview with Ken Liu |first=Luc |date=2013-03-25 |last=Reid |work=[[Strange Horizons]] |accessdate=2013-05-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530105508/http://www.strangehorizons.com/2013/20130325/1reid-a.shtml |archivedate=2013-05-30 }}</ref> In addition, his short story, \"Mono no aware\" won the 2013 [[Hugo Award]],<ref name=hugo2013>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2013-hugo-awards/ |title=2013 Hugo Awards |accessdate=4 September 2013 }}</ref><ref name=2013guardian>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2013/sep/02/hugo-awards-2013-science-fiction |title=The Hugo awards: 'beauty contest' or prize of the people? |author=David Barnett |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=4 September 2013 }}</ref> and his novella \"The Man Who Ended History: A Documentary\" was also nominated for a Hugo.<ref name=\"hugo2012\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2012-hugo-awards/ |title=2012 Hugo Awards |accessdate=4 September 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66nnsGGRI?url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2012-hugo-awards/ |archivedate=9 April 2012 }}</ref> The first novel in his ''The Dandelion Dynasty'' series, ''The Grace of Kings'', was a 2016 [[Nebula Award]] finalist.<ref>http://www.sfwa.org/2016/05/nebula-award-winners-announced-3/</ref> The novel was the 2016 [[Locus Award]] Best First Novel winner.<ref>{{cite web |title=2016 Locus Award Winners |url=https://locusmag.com/2016/06/2016-locus-awards-winners/ |website=locusmag.com |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nBesides his original work, Liu's translation of [[Liu Cixin]]'s [[Chinese language]] novel ''[[The Three-Body Problem (novel)|The Three-Body Problem]]'' (the first in the ''[[Remembrance of Earth's Past]]'' trilogy) won the 2015 [[Hugo Award for Best Novel]], making it the first translated novel to have won the award.<ref name=hugo2015>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2015-hugo-awards/ |title=2015 Hugo Awards |accessdate=2015-08-23 }}</ref> Liu also translated the third volume of the ''Remembrance of Earth's Past'' series, ''[[Death's End]],'' in 2016, which was a 2017 [[Hugo Award for Best Novel]] finalist.\n[[File:Taiyo Fujii, Ken Liu and Takayuki Tatsumi, at the Hugo Awards Ceremony 2017 at Worldcon in Helsinki.jpg|thumb|Ken Liu (center) at the Hugo Awards Ceremony 2017]]\n<br />\n\n===Winner===\n*2017 [[Locus Award]] for Best Collection, winner, The Paper Menagerie and Other Stories<ref>{{cite web |title=2017 Locus Award Winners |url=https://locusmag.com/2017/06/do-not-touch-2017-locus-awards-winners/ |website=locusmag.com |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n*2016 [[Locus Award]] for Best First Novel, winner, The Grace of Kings<ref>{{cite web |title=2016 Locus Award Winners |url=https://locusmag.com/2016/06/2016-locus-awards-winners/ |website=locusmag.com |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n*2015 [[Hugo Award for Best Novel]], winner, \"[[The Three-Body Problem (novel)|The Three-Body Problem]] (\u4e09\u4f53)\" by Cixin Liu, translated by Ken Liu<ref>{{Cite web|title = 2015 Hugo Awards|url = http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2015-hugo-awards/|website = The Hugo Awards|accessdate = 2015-10-11|language = en}}</ref>\n*2015 [[Sidewise Award for Alternate History]], winner, \"The Long Haul: From the Annals of Transportation, The Pacific Monthly, May 2009\"\n*2013 [[Hugo Award for Best Short Story]], winner, \"Mono no aware\"\n*2013 [[FantLab's Book of the Year Award|FantLab's Book of the Year Award for best Translated Novella or Short Story]], winner, \"Mono no aware\"\n*2013 [[FantLab's Book of the Year Award|FantLab's Book of the Year Award for best On-line publication in Small Form']], winner, \"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\"\n*2012 [[Science Fiction & Fantasy Translation Awards]], Short Form winner, translation from the Chinese of \"[http://clarkesworldmagazine.com/chen_08_11/ The Fish of Lijiang]\" by Chen Qiufan<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfftawards.org/?p=591 |title=2012 Winners |publisher=sfftawards.org |accessdate=June 1, 2012}}</ref>\n*2012 [[World Fantasy Award for Best Short Fiction]], winner, \"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\"\n*2012 [[Hugo Award for Best Short Story]], winner, \"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\"\n*2011 [[Nebula Award for Best Short Story]], winner, \"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\"\n\n===Nominated or finalist===\n*2017 [[Hugo Award for Best Novel]], finalist, \"[[Death's End]]\" by Cixin Liu, translated by Ken Liu<ref>{{Cite web|title = 2017 Hugo Awards|url = http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2017-hugo-awards/|website = The Hugo Awards|accessdate = 2017-10-11|language = en}}</ref>\n*2017 [[World Fantasy Convention|World Fantasy Award]], nominee, ''The Paper Menagerie and Other Stories'', Best Collection\n*2015 [[Locus Award]] for Best Novella, finalist, \"The Regular\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Locus Online News \u00bb 2015 Locus Awards Finalists|url = http://www.locusmag.com/News/2015/05/2015-locus-awards-finalists/|website = www.locusmag.com|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref>\n*2015 [[Theodore Sturgeon Award]], finalist, \"The Regular\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Gunn Center for the Study of Science Fiction News and Events|url = http://www.sfcenter.ku.edu/sturgeon-finalists.htm|website = Gunn Center for the Study of Science Fiction|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref>\n*2014 [[Nebula Award for Best Novel]], nominee, \"The Three-Body Problem (\u4e09\u4f53)\" by Cixin Liu, translated by Ken Liu<ref>{{Cite web|title = 2014 Nebula Awards Nominees Announced|url = http://www.sfwa.org/2015/02/2014-nebula-awards-nominees-announced/|website = SFWA|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref>\n*2014 [[Nebula Award for Best Novella]], nominee, \"The Regular\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = 2014 Nebula Awards Nominees Announced|url = http://www.sfwa.org/2015/02/2014-nebula-awards-nominees-announced/|website = SFWA|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref>\n*2014 [[Sidewise Award for Alternate History]], nominee, \"A Brief History of the Trans-Pacific Tunnel\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.locusmag.com/News/2014/06/2014-sidewise-award-finalists/ |title=2014 Sidewise Award Finalists |publisher=Locus|date=2014-06-06 |accessdate=2014-06-06}}</ref>\n*2014 [[Locus Award]] for Best Short Story, finalist, \"A Brief History of the Trans-Pacific Tunnel\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Locus Online News \u00bb 2014 Locus Awards Finalists|url = http://www.locusmag.com/News/2014/05/2014-locus-awards-finalists/|website = www.locusmag.com|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref>\n*2013 [[Locus Award]] for Best Short Story, finalist, \"Mono no aware\"\n*2013 [[Nebula Award for Best Novelette]], nominee, \"''The Litigation Master and the Monkey King\"\n*2013 [[Theodore Sturgeon Award]], finalist, \"The Bookmaking Habits of Select Species\" and \"Mono no aware\"\n*2012 [[Nebula Award for Best Short Story]], nominee, \"The Bookmaking Habits of Select Species\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = 2012 Nebula Awards Nominees Announced|url = https://www.sfwa.org/2013/02/2012-nebula-awards-nominees-announced/|website = SFWA|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref>\n*2012 [[Nebula Award for Best Novelette]], nominee, \"The Waves\"\n*2012 [[Nebula Award for Best Novella]], nominee, \"All the Flavors\"\n*2012 [[Theodore Sturgeon Award]], finalist, \"The Man Who Ended History: A Documentary\" and \"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\"\n*2012 [[Locus Award]] for Best Short Story, finalist, \"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\"\n*2012 [[Hugo Award for Best Novella]], nominee, \"The Man Who Ended History: A Documentary\"\n*2011 [[Nebula Award for Best Novella]], nominee, \"The Man Who Ended History: A Documentary\"\n\n==Original works==\n===Novels===\n====The Dandelion Dynasty====\n#{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/graceofkings0000liuk |author= |authorlink= |authormask= |title=The Grace of Kings |location= |publisher=Saga Press |year=2015 |isbn=9781481424271 |url-access=registration }}\n#{{cite book |url=http://www.simonandschuster.com/books/The-Wall-of-Storms/Ken-Liu/The-Dandelion-Dynasty/9781481424301 |author= |authorlink= |authormask= |title=The Wall of Storms |location= |publisher=Saga Press |year=2016 |isbn=9781481424301 }}\n\n====Misc.====\n*{{cite book |url=https://books.disney.com/book/legends-luke-skywalker/ |author= |authorlink= |authormask= |title=The Legends of Luke Skywalker |location= |publisher=Disney LucasFilm Press |year=2017 |isbn=978-1-4847-8077-0}}\n\n===Collections===\n*{{cite book |last1=Liu |first1=Ken |title=The Paper Menagerie and Other Stories |date=October 4, 2016 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |isbn=978-1481424363 |url=https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/The-Paper-Menagerie-and-Other-Stories/Ken-Liu/9781481424363}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Liu |first1=Ken |title=The Hidden Girl and Other Stories |date=February 25, 2020 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |isbn=978-1982134037 |url=https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/The-Hidden-Girl-and-Other-Stories/Ken-Liu/9781797102221}}\n\n===Short stories===\n<!-- Move entries below to table format below -->\n{|class='wikitable sortable' width='90%'\n|-\n!width=25%|Title\n!|Year\n!|First published\n!|Reprinted/collected\n!|Notes\n|-\n|The waves\n|2012\n|{{cite journal |author=Liu, Ken |authorlink= |authormask= |date=December 2012 |title=The waves |department= |journal=Asimov's Science Fiction |volume=36 |issue=12 |pages=38\u201351}}\n| \n|Novelette\n|-\n|The oracle\n|2013\n|{{cite journal |author=Liu, Ken |authorlink= |authormask= |date=Apr\u2013May 2013 |title=The oracle |department= |journal=Asimov's Science Fiction |volume=37 |issue=4&5 |pages=144\u2013152}}\n| \n|\n|-\n|The plantimal\n|2014\n|{{cite journal |author1=Resnick, Mike |authorlink1=Mike Resnick |author2=Ken Liu |last-author-amp=yes |date=March 2014 |title=The plantimal |department= |journal=Asimov's Science Fiction |volume=38 |issue=3 |pages=13\u201324}}\n|\n|\n|}\n* \"Thoughts and Prayers\", [https://slate.com/technology/2019/01/thoughts-and-prayers-ken-liu-short-story.html/ (online)] Slate.com, Jan. 26, 2019 \n* \"The Sith of Datawork\", ''From a Certain Point of View (Star Wars)'', October 3, 2017\n* \"The Long Haul: From the Annals of Transportation, The Pacific Monthly, May 2009\" [http://clarkesworldmagazine.com/liu_11_14/ (online)], ''[[Clarkesworld Magazine]]'', November 2014\n* \"Presence\" [http://uncannymagazine.com/article/presence/ (online)], ''Uncanny'', November/December 2014\n* \"Saboteur\", ''[[Analog Science Fiction and Fact|Analog]]'', December 2014\n* \"The Regular\", ''Upgraded'', edited by Neil Clarke, September 2014\n* \"The Gods Will Not Be Slain\", ''The End is Now'' (Book II of the ''Apocalypse Triptych''), edited by John Joseph Adams and Hugh Howey, September 2014\n* \"Running Shoes\" [http://sqmag.com/2014/08/31/edition-16-running-shoes-by-ken-liu/ (online)], ''SQ Mag'', Issue 16, September 2014\n* \"Homo Florensis\", ''Solaris Rising 3'', August 2014\n* \"In the Loop\", ''War Stories'', edited by Andrew Liptak and Jaym Gates, August 2014\n* \"Seventh Day of the Seventh Moon\" [http://www.tor.com/stories/2014/12/seventh-day-of-the-seventh-moon-ken-liu-reprint (online)], ''Kaleidoscope'', edited by Alisa Krasnostein and Julia Rios, August 2014\n* (with Lisa Tang Liu) \"Hark! Listen to the Animals\", ''Galaxy's Edge'', Issue 9, July 2014\n* \"What I Assume You Shall Assume\", ''Dead Man's Hand'', edited by John Joseph Adams, May 2014\n* \"Knotting Grass, Holding Ring\", ''Long Hidden'', edited by Rose Fox and [[Daniel Jos\u00e9 Older]], May 2014\n* \"Lecture 14: Concerning the Event Cloaking Device and Practical Applications Thereof\" [http://beta.cosmosmagazine.com/physical-sciences/event-cloak (online)], ''Cosmos'', April 2014\n* \"The Ten Suns\", ''Dark Expanse: Surviving the Collapse'', March 2014\n* \"The Gods Will Not Be Chained\", ''The End is Nigh'' (Book I of the ''Apocalypse Triptych''), edited by John Joseph Adams and Hugh Howey, March 2014\n* \"None Owns the Air\", ''Lightspeed Magazine'', February 2014\n* \"What Is Expected of a Wedding Host\" [http://dailysciencefiction.com/science-fiction/aliens/ken-liu/what-is-expected-of-a-wedding-host (online)], ''Daily Science Fiction'', February 2014\n* \"The Reborn\" [http://www.tor.com/stories/2014/01/reborn-ken-liu (online)], Tor.com, January 2014\n* \"Second Chance\" [http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v505/n7483/full/505448a.html (online)], ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'', January 2014\n* \"The Clockwork Soldier\" [http://clarkesworldmagazine.com/liu_01_14 (online)], ''[[Clarkesworld Magazine]]'', January 2014\n* \"You'll Always Have the Burden With You\", republished, [[Perihelion Science Fiction]], December 2013\n* \"The Litigation Master and the Monkey King\" [http://www.lightspeedmagazine.com/fiction/the-litigation-master-and-the-monkey-king/ (online)], ''[[Lightspeed Magazine]]'', August 2013\n* \"The Plague\", ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'', May 16, 2013\n* \"The Messenger's Tale\", ''Aoife's Kiss'', Issue 43, Winter 2012/2013 issue, December 2012\n* \"The Perfect Match\" [http://www.lightspeedmagazine.com/fiction/the-perfect-match/ (online)], ''[[Lightspeed Magazine]]'', December 2012\n* \"Good Hunting\", [https://web.archive.org/web/20121120182707/http://strangehorizons.com/fund_drives/2012/special-issue-hunting1-f.shtml (online)], ''[[Strange Horizons]]'', October 9, 2012\n* \"The Perfect Book\", ''[[Analog Science Fiction and Fact|Analog]]'', December 2012 issue, September 22, 2012\n* \"Arc\", ''[[F&SF]]'', September/October issue, September 2012\n* \"Summer Reading\", ''[[Daily Science Fiction]]'', September 4, 2012\n* \"Cutting\", ''[[Electric Velocipede]]'', Issue 24, July 30, 2012\n* \"You'll Always Have the Burden With You\", ''In Situ'', Dagan Books, July 10, 2012\n* \"Dear Emily\", ''The Memory Eater Anthology'', July 5, 2012\n* \"The Silk Merchant\", ''[[Apex Magazine|Apex]]'', Issue 38, July 3, 2012\n* \"Celestial Bodies\", ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'', June 28, 2012\n* \"Real Faces\", ''[[F&SF]]'', July/August issue, June 22, 2012\n* \"The Illusionist\" [http://goldfishgrimm.com/back-issues/issue-4-uncertain-principles/the-illusionist-ken-liu/ (online)], ''Goldfish Grimm's Spicy Fiction Sushi'', Issue 4, June 2, 2012 \n* \"Mono no aware\", ''The Future is Japanese'', May 15, 2012; republished [http://www.lightspeedmagazine.com/fiction/mono-no-aware/ (online)], ''[[Lightspeed Magazine]]'', June 2013\n* \"The Tome of Tourmaline\" [http://dailysciencefiction.com/fantasy/fantasy/ken-liu/the-tome-of-tourmaline (online)], ''[[Daily Science Fiction]]'', May 9, 2012\n* \"The Shadowcrafter\", ''Nine'', Issue 1, April 2012\n* \"Intelligent Design\" [http://www.schrodingersmouse.com/intelligent_design_by_ken_liu.html (online)], ''Schrodinger's Mouse'', April 2012\n* \"Monkeys\" [http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v484/n7394/full/484410a.html?WT.ec_id=NATURE-20120419 (online)], ''Nature's'' * \"Futures\" feature, April 19, 2012\n* \"To the Moon\", ''Fireside'', April 17, 2012\n* \"Memories of My Mother\" [http://dailysciencefiction.com/science-fiction/time-travel/ken-liu/memories-of-my-mother (online)], ''[[Daily Science Fiction]]'', March 19, 2012\n* \"All the Flavors\" [http://giganotosaurus.org/2012/02/ (online)], GigaNotoSaurus, February 2012\n* \"The Five Elements of the Heart Mind\" [http://www.lightspeedmagazine.com/fiction/the-five-elements-of-the-heart-mind/ (online)], ''[[Lightspeed Magazine]]'', January 24, 2012\n* \"Maxwell's Demon\", ''[[The Magazine of Fantasy & Science Fiction]]'', January/February 2012\n* \"The People of Pele\", ''[[Asimov's]]'', February 2012\n* \"The Last Summer\", ''10 Flash'', January 2012\n* \"The Necrocracy\", ''Penumbra'', December 2011\n* \"The Countable\", ''[[Asimov's]]'', December 2011\n* \"Justice FAIRBOT\", ''140 And Counting'', edited by Joanne Merriam, December 11, 2011\n* \"Life Plus Seventy\" [http://www.kasmamagazine.com/seventy.html (online)], '' Kasma SF'', November 23, 2011\n* \"Safe Empathy\", ''[[Daily Science Fiction]]'', November 21, 2011\n* \"Staying Behind\" [http://clarkesworldmagazine.com/liu_10_11/ (online)], ''[[Clarkesworld Magazine]]'', October 1, 2011\n* \"Golden Years in the Paleozoic\", ''[[Andromeda Spaceways Inflight Magazine]]'', Issue #52, September 2011\n* \"Real Artists\", TRSF (September 2011), a special publication of MIT's ''Technology Review''\n* \"The Last Seed\" [http://dailysciencefiction.com/story/ken-liu/the-last-seed (online)], ''[[Daily Science Fiction]]'', September 26, 2011\n* \"The Man Who Ended History: A Documentary\", ''Panverse Three'', edited by Dario Ciriello, September 2011\n* \"Music of the Spheres\", ''Mirror Shards: Exploring the Edges of Augmented Reality (Volume One)'', 2011\n* \"The Box That Eats Memories\" [http://dailysciencefiction.com/story/ken-liu/the-box-that-eats-memories (online)], ''[[Daily Science Fiction]]'', August 10, 2011\n* \"Hark! Listen to the Animals\", ''The ePocalypse: e-mails at the end'', co-written with Lisa Tang Liu, August 2011\n* \"The Caretaker\", ''Digital Science Fiction'', June 2011\n* \"Altogether Elsewhere, Vast Herds of Reindeer\", ''[[The Magazine of Fantasy & Science Fiction]]'', May/June 2011.\n* \"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\"  ''[[The Magazine of Fantasy & Science Fiction]]'', March/April 2011. \n* \"Ad Block\", [https://www.kasmamagazine.com/ad-block.html (online)], '' Kasma SF'', March 19, 2011\n* \"The Visit\" [https://web.archive.org/web/20110315204157/http://www.onthepremises.com/issue_13/story_13_1.html (online)], ''On the Premises'', March 2011 (Issue 13)\n* \"Simulacrum\" [http://www.lightspeedmagazine.com/fiction/simulacrum/ (online)], ''[[Lightspeed Magazine]]'', February 15, 2011\n* \"To the Stars\" [http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v470/n7332/full/470134a.html (online)], ''Nature's'' * \"Futures\" feature, co-written with Shelly Li, February 3, 2011\n* \"The Chase\", ''[[Every Day Fiction]]'', January 28, 2011\n* \"Tying Knots\" [http://clarkesworldmagazine.com/liu_01_11/ (online)], ''[[Clarkesworld Magazine]]'', January 2011\n* \"Saving Face\" [http://crossedgenres.com/archives/026-opposites/saving-face-by-shelly-li-and-ken-liu/ (online)], ''Crossed Genres'', co-written with Shelly Li, January 1, 2011\n* \"The Letter\" [http://www.everydayfiction.com/the-letter-by-ken-liu/ (online)], ''[[Every Day Fiction]]'', December 5, 2010\n* \"The Literomancer\", ''[[The Magazine of Fantasy & Science Fiction]]'', September/October 2010\n* \"The Phoenix\" [https://web.archive.org/web/20121014024818/http://www.onthepremises.com/issue_11/story_11_1.html (online)], ''On the Premises'', July 2010 (Issue 11)\n* \"Beidou (??)\", ''The Dragon and the Stars'', edited by Derwin Mak and Eric Choi, May 2010.\n* \"Single-Bit Error\", ''Thoughtcrime Experiments'', edited by Sumana Harihareswara and Leonard Richardson, 2009 (read) (buy); International Speculative Fiction, edited by Roberto Mendes, December 2013;\n* \"Beneath the Language\"  [https://web.archive.org/web/20100119084740/http://www.onthepremises.com/Issues_assets/On%20The%20Premises%20Issue%2002.pdf (online)], ''On the Premises'', July 2007 (Issue 2) \n* \"State Change\", ''Polyphony 4'', edited by Deborah Layne and Jay Lake, September 2004.\n* \"The Algorithms for Love\" [http://www.strangehorizons.com/2004/20040712/algorithms.shtml (online)], ''[[Strange Horizons]]'', July 2004; International Speculative Fiction, edited by Roberto Mendes, July 2012;\n* \"Gossamer\", ''Writers of the Future, Vol. 19'', 2003.\n* \"Carthaginian Rose\", ''Empire of Dreams and Miracles: [[The Phobos Science Fiction Anthology Volume 1]]'', edited by Orson Scott Card and Keith Olexa, 2002.\n* \"The Ussuri Bear\" [http://www.lightspeedmagazine.com/fiction/the-ussuri-bear/ (online)], Originally published in ''THE BEAST WITHIN 4'', edited by Jennifer Brozek, 2014\n\n==Notable English-language translations==\n===[[Remembrance of Earth's Past]] Series===\n* Book 1: ''[[The Three-Body Problem (novel)|The Three-Body Problem]]'', Tor Books, November 2014 (originally the [[Chinese language]] novel ''Three Body'', \u4e09\u4f53, 2008, by [[Liu Cixin]])\n* Book 3: ''[[Death's End]]'', Tor Books, September 2016 by Liu Cixin (originally the [[Chinese language]] novel ''Death's End'', \u6b7b\u795e\u6c38\u751f, 2010 by Liu Cixin)\n* Book 4: ''[[The Redemption of Time]]'', Tor Books, 2019 by Baoshu (originally a Chinese fanfic by Li Jun that was regularized by the original publisher Chongqing Press and series creator Cixin Liu; and published in 2011)<ref name=Verge-2018-10-19> {{cite magazine |url= https://www.theverge.com/2018/10/19/17990984/redemption-of-time-baoshu-cixin-liu-three-body-problem-science-fiction-book-cover-reveal |title= How a fan fiction for Cixin Liu's Three-Body Problem became an official novel |author= Andrew Liptak |date= 19 October 2018 |magazine= The Verge }} </ref>\n\n===Anthologies===\n* ''Invisible Planets'', Tor Books, November 2016\n* ''Broken Stars'', Tor Books, February 2019\n\n==Additional English-language translations==\n* \"Vagabonds\" by Hao Jingfang, April 2020\n* \"Waste Tide\" by Chen Quifan, April 2019 \n* \"Fields of Gold\" by Liu Cixin, May 2018\n* \"The Robot Who Liked to Tell Tall Tales\" by Fei Dao, [http://clarkesworldmagazine.com/fei_04_17/], ''[[Clarkesworld Magazine]]'', April 2017\n* \"The Snow of Jinyang\" by Zhang Ran, [http://clarkesworldmagazine.com/zhang_06_16/],''[[Clarkesworld Magazine]]'', June 2016\n* \"The Flowers of Shazui\" by Chen Qiufan, ''[[Interzone (magazine)|Interzone]]'', November 2012\n* \"Taking Care of God\" by Liu Cixin [https://archive.is/20130415063820/http://paper-republic.org/pubs/pathlight/2012-1/ (online)], ''[[Pathlight (magazine)|Pathlight]]'', March 2012\n* \"A Hundred Ghosts Parade Tonight\" by [[Xia Jia]] [http://clarkesworldmagazine.com/xia_02_12/ (online)], ''[[Clarkesworld Magazine]]'', February 2012\n* \"The City of Silence\" by Ma Boyong [https://worldsf.wordpress.com/2011/11/29/tuesday-fiction-the-city-of-silence-by-ma-boyong/ (online)], ''World SF Blog'', November 2011\n* \"The Mark Twain Robots\" by Ma Boyong, TRSF (September 2011), a special publication of MIT's ''Technology Review''\n* \"The Fish of Lijiang\" by Chen Qiufan [http://clarkesworldmagazine.com/chen_08_11/ (online)], ''[[Clarkesworld Magazine]]'', August 2011\n*\"Gathered in Translation\", an essay on  the process and subtleties of translating Chinese SF to English, and the reverse: [http://clarkesworldmagazine.com/liu_04_13/  online] at ''[[Clarkesworld Magazine]]'', April 2013\n\n==Liu's works in translation==\nMany of Liu's short stories have been translated into Chinese, Japanese, French, Spanish, and multiple other languages and published in short stories collections:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kenliu.name/stories/foreign-language-collections/ |title=Foreign Language Collections }}</ref>\n\n;Chinese\n* \u7231\u7684\u7b97\u6cd5 (\"Algorithms for Love and Others\"), published by SFW Publishing, September 5, 2012\n* \u601d\u7ef4\u7684\u5f62\u72b6 (\"The Shape of Thought and Others\"), published by [[Tsinghua University]] Press, November 11, 2014\n* \u6740\u654c\u7b97\u6cd5 (\"In the Loop and Others\"), published by SFW Publishing, March, 2015\n* \u5947\u70b9\u9057\u6c11 (\"Staying behind\")\uff0cpublished by Baror international, inc.. Armonk New York, U.S.A, 2017\n\n;Japanese\n* \u7d19\u306e\u52d5\u7269\u5712, published by [[SF Magazine|Hayakawa]], edited by \u53e4\u6ca2\u5609\u901a (Yoshimichi Furusawa), April 2015\n\n;French\n*  La M\u00e9nagerie de papier (\"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\") published by Editions du B\u00e9lial, edited by Ellen Herzfeld and Dominique Martel, 2015.\n*  Jardins de poussi\u00e8re (\"Dust gardens\") published by Editions du B\u00e9lial, edited by Ellen Herzfeld and Dominique Martel, 2019.\n\n;Spanish\n*  El zoo de papel y otros relatos (\"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\") published by Runas, Alianza Editorial, edited by Mar\u00eda Pilar San Rom\u00e1n Navarro, 2017.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official|kenliu.name}}\n* {{isfdb name}}\n*[http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/liu_ken \" Liu, Ken\"] (''[[The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction]]''; by [[Jonathan Clements]])\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/03/magazine/ken-liu-three-body-problem-chinese-science-fiction.html Ken Liu profile], NY Times Dec. 3, 2019.  Focuses on his translations of Chinese SF.\n{{Hugo Award Best Novel}}\n{{Hugo Award Best Short Story 2001\u20132020}}\n{{Nebula Award for Best Short Story}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liu, Ken}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:American male short story writers]]\n[[Category:American science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American short story writers]]\n[[Category:American speculative fiction translators]]\n[[Category:American writers of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Asimov's Science Fiction people]]\n[[Category:Chinese\u2013English translators]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Hugo Award-winning writers]]\n[[Category:Nebula Award winners]]\n[[Category:Sidewise Award winners]]\n[[Category:World Fantasy Award-winning writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| name        = Ken Liu\n| image       = Ken Liu 2016.jpg\n| caption     = Liu at the 2016 Texas Book Festival\n| birth_name  = {{zh|c=\u5218\u5b87\u6606|p=Li\u00fa Y\u01d4k\u016bn|labels=no}}\n| birth_date  = 1976\n| birth_place = [[Lanzhou]], China\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = Author, translator, lawyer, programmer\n| nationality = American\n| period      = \n| genre       = [[Science fiction]], [[fantasy]]\n| subject     = \n| movement    = \n| notableworks= {{Plainlist}}\n* ''[[The Paper Menagerie]]'' (2011)\n* ''The Grace of Kings'' (2015)\n* ''[[The Three-Body Problem (novel)|The Three-Body Problem]]'' (2015 {{abbr|transl.|translation into English}})\n* \"[[Byzantine Empathy]]\" (2018 short)\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| spouse      = Lisa Tang Liu<ref name=strangehorizons />\n| children    = \n| relatives   = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| awards      = {{Plainlist}}\n* [[Hugo Award]]s (\u00d73)\n* [[Locus Award]]s (\u00d72)\n* [[FantLab's Book of the Year Award|FantLab's Award]]s (\u00d72)\n* [[Nebula Award]] (\u00d71)\n* [[Sidewise Award for Alternate History|Sidewise Award]] (\u00d71)\n* [[World Fantasy Award]] (\u00d71)\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| signature   = \n| website     = {{Official URL}}\n| portaldisp  = \n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese|t=\u5289\u5b87\u6606|s=\u5218\u5b87\u6606|p=Li\u00fa Y\u01d4k\u016bn}}\n\n'''Ken Liu''' (born 1976) is an award-winning [[Americans|American]] author of [[science-fiction]] and [[fantasy]], as well as a translator, lawyer, and computer programmer.  His epic fantasy series ''The Dandelion Dynasty'', the first work in the \"silkpunk\" genre, is published by [[Simon & Schuster]].<ref name=\"tordotcomsummary\">{{cite web |title=Ken Liu Talks Silkpunk, Old Poems, and Contemporary Chinese SFF in His Reddit AMA |url=https://www.tor.com/2015/04/13/ken-liu-reddit-ama-highlights/ |website=Tor.com}}</ref> His short stories have appeared in ''[[F&SF]]'', ''[[Asimov's]]'', ''[[Analog Science Fiction and Fact|Analog]]'', ''[[Lightspeed (magazine)|Lightspeed]]'', ''[[Clarkesworld]]'', and multiple \"Year's Best\" anthologies.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Clarkesworld Magazine - Science Fiction & Fantasy|url = http://clarkesworldmagazine.com/awards_and_recognition/|website = Clarkesworld Magazine|accessdate = 2015-10-11|language = en}}</ref>\n\n==Childhood and career==\nLiu was born in 1976 in [[Lanzhou]], [[China]].<ref name=\"nw103016\"/> He spent his childhood with his grandparents.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ken Liu Talks Silkpunk, Old Poems, and Contemporary Chinese SFF in His Reddit AMA |url=https://www.tor.com/2015/04/13/ken-liu-reddit-ama-highlights/ |website=Tor.com |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref> His mother, who received her Ph.D. in Chemistry in the United States, is a pharmaceutical chemist, while his father is a computer engineer.<ref name=\"asiaone\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.asiaone.com/ken-liu-won-science-fiction-awards-best-short-story?nopaging=1\n|title=Ken Liu won science fiction awards for best short story\n|accessdate=2019-01-05\n|date=2013-09-09\n|publisher=[[AsiaOne]]\n}}</ref> The family emigrated to the United States when Liu was 11 years old.<ref name=\"nw103016\">{{cite web\n|url=https://www.newsweek.com/man-bringing-chinese-science-fiction-west-514893\n|title=MEET THE MAN BRINGING CHINESE SCIENCE FICTION TO THE WEST\n|accessdate=2019-01-05\n|date=2016-10-30\n|publisher=[[Newsweek]]\n}}</ref> They lived in [[California]] and [[Stonington, Connecticut|Stonington]] before settling in [[Waterford, Connecticut|Waterford]]. Liu graduated from [[Waterford High School (Connecticut)|Waterford High School]] in 1994, where he ran cross-country and track.<ref name=\"day\">{{cite web\n|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20150414/ENT02/150419746\n|title=Waterford alum \u2014 and award-winning short story writer \u2014 Ken Liu releases his debut novel\n|accessdate=2019-01-05\n|date=2015-04-14\n|publisher=[[The Day (New London)]]\n}}</ref> At [[Harvard College]], he studied English Literature and Computer Science, receiving his A. B. in 1998.<ref name=\"day\"/><ref name=hm>{{cite web\n|url=https://harvardmagazine.com/2016/11/fusion-fantasy\n|title=Fusion Fantasy:Ken Liu's sprawling hybrid fiction\n|accessdate=2019-01-05\n|date=November\u2013December 2016\n|publisher=[[Harvard Magazine]]\n}}</ref> After graduation, he worked as a software engineer for [[Microsoft]], and then joined a start-up in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]. He later received his J.D. from [[Harvard Law School]] in 2004 and after working as a corporate lawyer, eventually became a high-tech litigation consultant.<ref name=\"day\"/><ref name=hm/> He began publishing fiction in 2002. His first published work was \"Carthaginian Rose\", a short story on [[mind uploading]] which was published alongside nine other authors in [[The Phobos Science Fiction Anthology Volume 1]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Ken |title=Carthaginian Rose |url=https://kenliu.name/stories/carthaginian-rose/ |website=Ken Liu, Writer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214061409/https://kenliu.name/stories/carthaginian-rose/ |archive-date=14 December 2019 |accessdate=14 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter a long career writing and publishing short fiction, Liu turned to epic fantasy novels, starting with ''The Grace of Kings'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Interview: Ken Liu |url=http://www.lightspeedmagazine.com/nonfiction/interview-ken-liu/ |website=Lightspeed |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref> He has also written for the [[Star Wars]] universe, with ''The Legends of Luke Skywalker'' in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=Interview on The Legends of Luke Skywalker |url=https://www.starwars.com/news/ken-liu-exploring-perfect-mythic-figure-the-legends-of-luke-skywalker |website=StarWars.com |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlong with his original work, Ken Liu has found work in translating. He has translated the works of multiple Chinese authors into English, including [[w: Liu Cixin| Liu Cixin]], [[w:Hao Jingfang|Hao Jingfang]], [[w: Chen Qiufan| Chen Qiufan]], [[w:Xia Jia| Xia Jia]], and others.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chinese SF and the art of translation |url=http://blogs.nature.com/futureconditional/2016/08/20/chinese-sf-and-the-art-of-translation-a-qa-with-ken-liu/ |website=Nature.com |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>. His translation of ''[[w: The Three-Body Problem (novel)|The Three Body Problem]]'' by Liu Cixin helped the book become a best seller to English readers.<ref>{{cite web |title=How Ken Liu went from engineer to lawyer to SF writer to the foremost translator of Chinese sf into English| url=https://boingboing.net/2019/12/04/rod-serling-w-chinese-characte.html |website= boingboing.net |accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> He also has worked on editing works. While editing the anthology ''Invisible Planets'', Ken Liu translated the stories contained within it from Chinese into English. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://electricliterature.com/ken-liu-will-keep-an-open-mind/|title=Ken Liu Will Keep an Open Mind|website=electricliterature.com|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome of Liu's work have been adapted into visual media. \"Memories of My Mother,\" a short story, was the basis of \"Beautiful Dreamer\" by David Gaddie.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4794788/ |website=IMDB |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref> \"Real Artists,\" a short story, was adapted into a short film by Cameo Wood.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5648094/ |website=IMDB}}</ref> \"Good Hunting,\" a short story, was adapted into an animated short as part of [[Netflix]]'s ''[[Love, Death & Robots]]'' series in 2019.\n\n==Awards==\n\nLiu's short story \"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\" is the first work of fiction, of any length, to win the Nebula, Hugo, and World Fantasy Awards.<ref name=\"strangehorizons\">{{cite web |url=http://www.strangehorizons.com/2013/20130325/1reid-a.shtml |title=Not Just Vast Armies Clashing on Dark Plains at Night: An Interview with Ken Liu |first=Luc |date=2013-03-25 |last=Reid |work=[[Strange Horizons]] |accessdate=2013-05-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530105508/http://www.strangehorizons.com/2013/20130325/1reid-a.shtml |archivedate=2013-05-30 }}</ref> In addition, his short story, \"Mono no aware\" won the 2013 [[Hugo Award]],<ref name=hugo2013>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2013-hugo-awards/ |title=2013 Hugo Awards |accessdate=4 September 2013 }}</ref><ref name=2013guardian>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2013/sep/02/hugo-awards-2013-science-fiction |title=The Hugo awards: 'beauty contest' or prize of the people? |author=David Barnett |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=4 September 2013 }}</ref> and his novella \"The Man Who Ended History: A Documentary\" was also nominated for a Hugo.<ref name=\"hugo2012\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2012-hugo-awards/ |title=2012 Hugo Awards |accessdate=4 September 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66nnsGGRI?url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2012-hugo-awards/ |archivedate=9 April 2012 }}</ref> The first novel in his ''The Dandelion Dynasty'' series, ''The Grace of Kings'', was a 2016 [[Nebula Award]] finalist.<ref>http://www.sfwa.org/2016/05/nebula-award-winners-announced-3/</ref> The novel was the 2016 [[Locus Award]] Best First Novel winner.<ref>{{cite web |title=2016 Locus Award Winners |url=https://locusmag.com/2016/06/2016-locus-awards-winners/ |website=locusmag.com |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nBesides his original work, Liu's translation of [[Liu Cixin]]'s [[Chinese language]] novel ''[[The Three-Body Problem (novel)|The Three-Body Problem]]'' (the first in the ''[[Remembrance of Earth's Past]]'' trilogy) won the 2015 [[Hugo Award for Best Novel]], making it the first translated novel to have won the award.<ref name=hugo2015>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2015-hugo-awards/ |title=2015 Hugo Awards |accessdate=2015-08-23 }}</ref> Liu also translated the third volume of the ''Remembrance of Earth's Past'' series, ''[[Death's End]],'' in 2016, which was a 2017 [[Hugo Award for Best Novel]] finalist.\n[[File:Taiyo Fujii, Ken Liu and Takayuki Tatsumi, at the Hugo Awards Ceremony 2017 at Worldcon in Helsinki.jpg|thumb|Ken Liu at the Hugo Awards Ceremony 2017]]\n<br />\n\n===Winner===\n*2017 [[Locus Award]] for Best Collection, winner, The Paper Menagerie and Other Stories<ref>{{cite web |title=2017 Locus Award Winners |url=https://locusmag.com/2017/06/do-not-touch-2017-locus-awards-winners/ |website=locusmag.com |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n*2016 [[Locus Award]] for Best First Novel, winner, The Grace of Kings<ref>{{cite web |title=2016 Locus Award Winners |url=https://locusmag.com/2016/06/2016-locus-awards-winners/ |website=locusmag.com |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n*2015 [[Hugo Award for Best Novel]], winner, \"[[The Three-Body Problem (novel)|The Three-Body Problem]] (\u4e09\u4f53)\" by Cixin Liu, translated by Ken Liu<ref>{{Cite web|title = 2015 Hugo Awards|url = http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2015-hugo-awards/|website = The Hugo Awards|accessdate = 2015-10-11|language = en}}</ref>\n*2015 [[Sidewise Award for Alternate History]], winner, \"The Long Haul: From the Annals of Transportation, The Pacific Monthly, May 2009\"\n*2013 [[Hugo Award for Best Short Story]], winner, \"Mono no aware\"\n*2013 [[FantLab's Book of the Year Award|FantLab's Book of the Year Award for best Translated Novella or Short Story]], winner, \"Mono no aware\"\n*2013 [[FantLab's Book of the Year Award|FantLab's Book of the Year Award for best On-line publication in Small Form']], winner, \"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\"\n*2012 [[Science Fiction & Fantasy Translation Awards]], Short Form winner, translation from the Chinese of \"[http://clarkesworldmagazine.com/chen_08_11/ The Fish of Lijiang]\" by Chen Qiufan<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfftawards.org/?p=591 |title=2012 Winners |publisher=sfftawards.org |accessdate=June 1, 2012}}</ref>\n*2012 [[World Fantasy Award for Best Short Fiction]], winner, \"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\"\n*2012 [[Hugo Award for Best Short Story]], winner, \"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\"\n*2011 [[Nebula Award for Best Short Story]], winner, \"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\"\n\n===Nominated or finalist===\n*2017 [[Hugo Award for Best Novel]], finalist, \"[[Death's End]]\" by Cixin Liu, translated by Ken Liu<ref>{{Cite web|title = 2017 Hugo Awards|url = http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2017-hugo-awards/|website = The Hugo Awards|accessdate = 2017-10-11|language = en}}</ref>\n*2017 [[World Fantasy Convention|World Fantasy Award]], nominee, ''The Paper Menagerie and Other Stories'', Best Collection\n*2015 [[Locus Award]] for Best Novella, finalist, \"The Regular\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Locus Online News \u00bb 2015 Locus Awards Finalists|url = http://www.locusmag.com/News/2015/05/2015-locus-awards-finalists/|website = www.locusmag.com|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref>\n*2015 [[Theodore Sturgeon Award]], finalist, \"The Regular\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Gunn Center for the Study of Science Fiction News and Events|url = http://www.sfcenter.ku.edu/sturgeon-finalists.htm|website = Gunn Center for the Study of Science Fiction|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref>\n*2014 [[Nebula Award for Best Novel]], nominee, \"The Three-Body Problem (\u4e09\u4f53)\" by Cixin Liu, translated by Ken Liu<ref>{{Cite web|title = 2014 Nebula Awards Nominees Announced|url = http://www.sfwa.org/2015/02/2014-nebula-awards-nominees-announced/|website = SFWA|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref>\n*2014 [[Nebula Award for Best Novella]], nominee, \"The Regular\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = 2014 Nebula Awards Nominees Announced|url = http://www.sfwa.org/2015/02/2014-nebula-awards-nominees-announced/|website = SFWA|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref>\n*2014 [[Sidewise Award for Alternate History]], nominee, \"A Brief History of the Trans-Pacific Tunnel\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.locusmag.com/News/2014/06/2014-sidewise-award-finalists/ |title=2014 Sidewise Award Finalists |publisher=Locus|date=2014-06-06 |accessdate=2014-06-06}}</ref>\n*2014 [[Locus Award]] for Best Short Story, finalist, \"A Brief History of the Trans-Pacific Tunnel\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Locus Online News \u00bb 2014 Locus Awards Finalists|url = http://www.locusmag.com/News/2014/05/2014-locus-awards-finalists/|website = www.locusmag.com|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref>\n*2013 [[Locus Award]] for Best Short Story, finalist, \"Mono no aware\"\n*2013 [[Nebula Award for Best Novelette]], nominee, \"''The Litigation Master and the Monkey King\"\n*2013 [[Theodore Sturgeon Award]], finalist, \"The Bookmaking Habits of Select Species\" and \"Mono no aware\"\n*2012 [[Nebula Award for Best Short Story]], nominee, \"The Bookmaking Habits of Select Species\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = 2012 Nebula Awards Nominees Announced|url = https://www.sfwa.org/2013/02/2012-nebula-awards-nominees-announced/|website = SFWA|accessdate = 2015-10-11}}</ref>\n*2012 [[Nebula Award for Best Novelette]], nominee, \"The Waves\"\n*2012 [[Nebula Award for Best Novella]], nominee, \"All the Flavors\"\n*2012 [[Theodore Sturgeon Award]], finalist, \"The Man Who Ended History: A Documentary\" and \"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\"\n*2012 [[Locus Award]] for Best Short Story, finalist, \"[[The Paper Menagerie]]\"\n*2012 [[Hugo Award for Best Novella]], nominee, \"The Man Who Ended History: A Documentary\"\n*2011 [[Nebula Award for Best Novella]], nominee, \"The Man Who Ended History: A Documentary\"\n\n==Original works==\n===Novels===\n====The Dandelion Dynasty====\n#{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/graceofkings0000liuk |author= |authorlink= |authormask= |title=The Grace of Kings |location= |publisher=Saga Press |year=2015 |isbn=9781481424271 |url-access=registration }}\n#{{cite book |url=http://www.simonandschuster.com/books/The-Wall-of-Storms/Ken-Liu/The-Dandelion-Dynasty/9781481424301 |author= |authorlink= |authormask= |title=The Wall of Storms |location= |publisher=Saga Press |year=2016 |isbn=9781481424301 }}\n\n====Misc.====\n*{{cite book |url=https://books.disney.com/book/legends-luke-skywalker/ |author= |authorlink= |authormask= |title=The Legends of Luke Skywalker |location= |publisher=Disney LucasFilm Press |year=2017 |isbn=978-1-4847-8077-0}}\n\n===Collections===\n*{{cite book |last1=Liu |first1=Ken |title=The Paper Menagerie and Other Stories |date=October 4, 2016 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |isbn=978-1481424363 |url=https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/The-Paper-Menagerie-and-Other-Stories/Ke