ult     = W\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n| round      = S-F, 2nd leg\n| date       = 8 March 1995\n| time       = 19:45\n| team1      = [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]\n| score      = 0\u20131\n| report     = [http://www.lfchistory.net/SeasonArchive/Game/1929 Report]\n| team2      = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| goals1     = \n| goals2     = [[Robbie Fowler|Fowler]] {{goal|27}}\n| location   = [[London]]\n| stadium    = [[Selhurst Park]]\n| attendance = 18,224\n| referee    =\n| result     = W\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n| round      = [[1995 Football League Cup Final|Final]]\n| date       = 2 April 1995\n| time       = 17:00\n| team1      = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| score      = 2\u20131\n| report     = [http://www.lfchistory.net/SeasonArchive/Game/1933 Report]\n| team2      = [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]\n| goals1     = [[Steve McManaman|McManaman]] {{goal|37||68}}\n| goals2     = [[Alan Thompson (footballer born 1973)|Thompson]] {{goal|70}}\n| location   = [[London]]\n| stadium    = [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]]\n| attendance = 75,595\n| referee    = [[Philip Don]] ([[Middlesex County Football Association|Middlesex]])\n| result     = W\n}}\n\n==Statistics==\n\n===''Goals''===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!width=15|{{Tooltip|Rank|Rank}}\n!width=15|{{Tooltip|No.|Squad Number}}\n!width=15|{{Tooltip|Pos|Position}}\n!width=15|{{Tooltip|Nat|Nationality}}\n!width=145|Name\n!width=80|[[1994\u201395 FA Premier League|Premier League]]\n!width=80|[[1994\u201395 FA Cup|FA Cup]]\n!width=80|[[1994\u201395 Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n!width=80|Total\n|-\n|'''1'''\n|23\n|[[Forward (association football)|FW]]\n|{{flagicon|ENG}}\n|align=left|[[Robbie Fowler]]\n|25\n|2\n|4\n|'''31'''\n|-\n|'''2'''\n|9\n|[[Forward (association football)|FW]]\n|{{flagicon|WAL}}\n|align=left|[[Ian Rush]]\n|12\n|1\n|6\n|'''19'''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|'''3'''\n|10\n|[[Midfielder|MF]]\n|{{flagicon|ENG}}\n|align=left|[[John Barnes (footballer)|John Barnes]]\n|7\n|2\n|0\n|'''9'''\n|-\n|17\n|[[Midfielder|MF]]\n|{{flagicon|ENG}}\n|align=left|[[Steve McManaman]]\n|7\n|0\n|2\n|'''9'''\n|-\n|'''5'''\n|15\n|[[Midfielder|MF]]\n|{{flagicon|ENG}}\n|align=left|[[Jamie Redknapp]]\n|3\n|1\n|2\n|'''6'''\n|-\n|'''6'''\n|12\n|[[Defender (association football)|DF]]\n|{{flagicon|ENG}}\n|align=left|[[John Scales]]\n|2\n|0\n|1\n|'''3'''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|'''7'''\n|14\n|[[Midfielder|MF]]\n|{{flagicon|DEN}}\n|align=left|[[Jan M\u00f8lby]] \n|2\n|0\n|0\n|'''2'''\n|-\n|25\n|[[Defender (association football)|DF]]\n|{{flagicon|ENG}}\n|align=left|[[Neil Ruddock]]\n|2\n|0\n|0\n|'''2'''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|'''9'''\n|7\n|[[Midfielder|MF]]\n|{{flagicon|ENG}}\n|align=left|[[Nigel Clough]]\n|0\n|0\n|1\n|'''1'''\n|-\n|22\n|[[Defender (association football)|DF]]\n|{{flagicon|ENG}}\n|align=left|[[Steve Harkness]]\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|'''1'''\n|-\n|colspan=5|'''Own goal'''\n|4\n|0\n|0\n|'''4'''\n|-\n|colspan=5|'''Totals'''\n|'''65'''\n|'''6'''\n|'''16'''\n|'''87'''\n|}\n\n==Events of the season==\n\n===August===\nThe only major signing of the season was that of Danish goalkeeper Michael Stensgaard as understudy to David James, following Bruce Grobbelaar's departure to Southampton. Defender Julian Dicks had returned to West Ham United after an unsuccessful season at Anfield, followed by midfielder Don Hutchison just after the start of the season, around the same time that veteran Ronnie Whelan called time on 15 years at Anfield and signed for Southend United.\n\nThe league campaign began in style with a 6-1 away win over newly promoted [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in which Ian Rush and Steve McManaman both scored twice, with Robbie Fowler and Jan Molby scoring the other goals. [[Robbie Fowler]] then managed a hat-trick in less than five minutes in the next game, when Liverpool beat [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 3-0 at Anfield. Fowler was on target again, along with John Barnes, in the next game - a 2-0 win at [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].\n\n===September===\nThe month began with Roy Evans breaking the national defender transfer fee with a \u00a33.6 million move for Wimbledon's John Scales, followed 24 hours later by a \u00a33.5 million signing of Coventry's Phil Babb.\n\nLiverpool saw league action just three times in September, and failed to record any wins. The first game was a goalless draw at home to West Ham, followed by a 2-0 defeat at Manchester United before Ian Rush scored Liverpool's only league goal of the month in a 1-1 away draw with [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]. The Reds were sixth in the league, which was being led by Newcastle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpool-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=24&Month=Sep&ssnno=124&teamno=342 |title=Snapshot Tables 1994-1995 24 Sep Liverpool - Liverpool FC - LFC Online |publisher=Liverpool-mad.co.uk |date=24 September 1994 |accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe League Cup quest began on 21 September, in which John Scales scored his first goal for the club and was joined on the scoresheet by Robbie Fowler in a 2-0 second-round first-leg win over [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] at [[Turf Moor]].<ref name=\"liverweb1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.liverweb.org.uk/season.asp?season=199495 |title=Liverpool Results 1994-95 |publisher=Liverweb |date= |accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===October===\nOctober saw mixed results for Liverpool, who were beaten 3-2 by [[Kenny Dalglish]]'s title chasers [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] at [[Ewood Park]] before recording a 3-0 home win over Wimbledon and a 3-1 away win over [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]. The month ended on a sour note with a 2-1 defeat at [[Queen's Park Rangers F.C.|QPR]].\n\nLiverpool eliminated Burnley from the League Cup with a 4-1 win in the second leg, in which Jamie Redknapp was on the scoresheet twice and [[Nigel Clough]] scored what would be his only goal of the season. In the next round, Ian Rush scored twice as the Reds defeated [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] 2-1 at Anfield.<ref name=\"liverweb1\"/>\n\nThe Reds ended October in fifth place, with Newcastle still leading the way, newly promoted [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] second and pushing hard for a rare title one season after promotion, followed by Manchester United and Blackburn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpool-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=31&Month=Oct&ssnno=124&teamno=342 |title=Snapshot Tables 1994-1995 31 Oct Liverpool - Liverpool FC - LFC Online |publisher=Liverpool-mad.co.uk |date=31 October 1994 |accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===November===\nA goal from [[Robbie Fowler]] on 5 November gave Liverpool a 1-0 home win over fellow title challengers Nottingham Forest at Anfield. Fowler then scored twice in the next game, a 3-1 win home win over Chelsea. Liverpool were then on the losing side in the [[Merseyside derby]] at [[Goodison Park]], where a struggling [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] won 2-0. The month ended with a 1-1 home draw against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]. The League Cup quest continued at the end of the month when an Ian Rush hat-trick disposed of Blackburn in the fourth round at [[Ewood Park]].<ref name=\"liverweb1\"/> The Reds ended the month fourth in the Premier League, six points behind leaders Blackburn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpool-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=26&Month=Nov&ssnno=124&teamno=342 |title=Snapshot Tables 1994-1995 26 Nov Liverpool - Liverpool FC - LFC Online |publisher=Liverpool-mad.co.uk |date=26 November 1994 |accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===December===\nLiverpool were unbeaten in the six league games they played in December, but the first three of those were draws so the subsequent wins over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] restricted them to third place in the league when wins from those first three games would have put them just one point behind leaders Blackburn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpool-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=31&Month=Dec&ssnno=124&teamno=342 |title=Snapshot Tables 1994-1995 31 Dec Liverpool - Liverpool FC - LFC Online |publisher=Liverpool-mad.co.uk |date=31 December 1994 |accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===January===\nThe first month of 1995 saw the departure of Liverpool's longest serving player [[Steve Nicol]], who signed for Division One strugglers [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] after losing his place in the first team to new arrivals John Scales and Phil Babb.\n\nHowever, the year began on a bright note with a 4-0 home win over [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]. Then came a 1-0 defeat at home to struggling Ipswich, followed by a goalless draw in the second Merseyside derby of the season at Anfield.\n\nThere was success in the cup competitions as an Ian Rush goal gave the Reds 1-0 win over Arsenal in the League Cup quarter-final. However, it took a penalty shoot-out in a replay to see off Division Two underdogs [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] in the FA Cup third round, while Division One strugglers Burnley faced Liverpool again after the League Cup meeting to hold the Reds to a goalless draw at Turf Moor, forcing yet another replay against lower league opposition.<ref name=\"liverweb1\"/>\n\n===February===\nAnother quiet month for league action saw the Reds held to 1-1 draws with Forest and QPR before scraping to a 2-1 win away to Sheffield Wednesday. As had happened last month, the biggest news for Liverpool was in the cup competitions. The FA Cup fourth round replay saw them overcome Burnley 1-0, before a fifth round clash with Wimbledon ended in a 1-1 draw and forced another replay, which the Reds won 2-0. Then came the League Cup semi-final first leg at Anfield, in which a Robbie Fowler goal saw the Reds defeat [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] (battling relegation but chasing glory in both cup competitions) 1-0.<ref name=\"liverweb1\"/>\n\nIt was looking too late for Liverpool to challenge for a league title win and a unique domestic treble, as they were now 15 points behind leaders Blackburn (though they did have two games in hnd) and occupying fourth place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpool-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=25&Month=Feb&ssnno=124&teamno=342 |title=Snapshot Tables 1994-1995 25 Feb Liverpool - Liverpool FC - LFC Online |publisher=Liverpool-mad.co.uk |date=25 February 1995 |accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===March===\nMarch brought the familiar pattern for Liverpool of mixed results in the league but good form in the cups. Wins over title hopefuls Manchester United and Newcastle but a home defeat by relegation-threatened Coventry and an away draw with Tottenham Hotspur saw them fall to fifth place in the table and leave their title hopes almost completely dead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpool-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=22&Month=Mar&ssnno=124&teamno=342 |title=Snapshot Tables 1994-1995 22 Mar Liverpool - Liverpool FC - LFC Online |publisher=Liverpool-mad.co.uk |date=22 March 1995 |accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref> The FA Cup fifth round replay against Wimbledon saw Liverpool win 2-0, but their hopes of glory ended in the quarter-finals when they 2-1 at home to Tottenham Hotspur. However, the League Cup campaign continued with another 1-0 win over Crystal Palace and another goal from Robbie Fowler in the second leg of the semi-final, to book the Reds a [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]] date with [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] and a chance of becoming the first team to win the League Cup five times.<ref name=\"liverweb1\"/>\n\n===April===\nThe League Cup final at [[Wembley Stadium]] on 2 April 1995 saw Liverpool beat Bolton 2-1 with a brace from Steve McManaman giving Roy Evans the first major trophy of his managerial career, and Liverpool's first major trophy since the FA Cup in 1992. With a place in the [[UEFA Cup]] guaranteed for next season and the title now beyond reasonable hope for Liverpool, there was less pressure on them in the final few games of the season, and they looked well placed to finish higher in the league than they had in any of the previous three seasons. Four wins and two defeats from six games made the previously crucial top-five finish a near certainty anyway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpool-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=29&Month=Apr&ssnno=124&teamno=342 |title=Snapshot Tables 1994-1995 29 Apr Liverpool - Liverpool FC - LFC Online |publisher=Liverpool-mad.co.uk |date=29 April 1995 |accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===May===\nA draw with Wimbledon and defeats to two sides climbing clear of relegation danger (Aston Villa and West Ham United) were of little importance to a Liverpool side who could no longer win the title but had already booked European action with their League Cup glory. There was, however, one more game left to play. The final game of the league season was at Anfield on 14 May, and the opponents were Blackburn. Kenny Dalglish's new team were two points ahead of Manchester United - the last side capable of catching them - and a win for them would secure their first league title since 1914. However, if they lost or drew and Manchester United won at West Ham, the title would remain at [[Old Trafford]] for the third successive season. There was speculation that Liverpool would give their old manager an easy ride and let him add to the three title success he had managed them to in his time there, but Roy Evans dismissed such talk and his Liverpool side defeated Dalglish's men 2-1. The stadium was a scene of jubilation after the final whistle when news came through that the game in east London had ended in a 1-1 draw and Blackburn had ended their 81-year title wait.<ref name=\"liverweb1\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=notes|colwidth=30em}}\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n*{{cite web|author=Season Archive |url=http://www.lfchistory.net/SeasonArchive/Games/36 |title=Games for the 1994-1995 season |publisher=LFChistory.net |date= |accessdate=6 October 2012}}\n{{Liverpool F.C. seasons}}\n{{1994\u201395 in English football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1994-95 Liverpool F.C. season}}\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. seasons]]\n[[Category:1994\u201395 FA Premier League by team|Liverpool]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Andy Clarke", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1994%E2%80%9395_Liverpool_F.C._season"}
{"title_page": "Priyavrat Singh", "text_new": "\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                      = [[Priyavrat Singh]]\n| image                     = [[File:Priyavrat singh.jpg|Priyavrat singh]]\n| caption                   = \n| birth_date                = 5 December 1977<ref>https://www.mpinfo.org/mpinfostatic/english/council/cabinetmin/Shri-Priyavrat-Singh.asp</ref>\n| birth_place               = [[Indore]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| residence                 = [[Khilchipur]]\n| nationality               = [[Indian]]\n| citizenship               = [[India]]\n| office1                   = [[Kamal Nath ministry|Cabinet Minister ]]<br>[[Government of Madhya Pradesh]]\n| party                     = [[Indian National Congress]]\n}}\n\n\n'''Priyavrat Singh''' (born 5 December 1977 ) is an Indian politician who served as a member of [[Indian National Congress]] as the [[Member Of Legislative Assembly|Member of Legislative Assembly]] of [[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly|Madhya Pradhesh]] in 2003 and was re-elected in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elections.in/madhya-pradesh/assembly-constituencies/2008-election-results.html|title=Madhya Pradesh Assembly Election Results in 2008|website=www.elections.in|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> He served the constituency of [[Khilchipur (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Khilchipur Vidhan Sabha]] and was a  [[Cabinet minister]] of MP Govt. He is also Known as Raja of [[Khilchipur]].<ref>http://www.indianrajputs.com/view/khilchipur</ref>\n\n==Political Career==\nHe served as a Cabinet Minister in the [[Kamal Nath ministry|'''Kamal Nath ministry''']] of Madhya Pradesh Government, between December 2018 and March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mpinfo.org/mpinfostatic/english/council/cabinetmin/Shri-Priyavrat-Singh.asp|title=::Department Of Public Relations,Madhya Pradesh::|website=www.mpinfo.org|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians from Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Indore]]\n[[Category:Madhya Pradesh MLAs 2008\u20132013]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n\n{{India-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                      = [[Priyavrat Singh]]\n| image                     = [[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Priyavrat_singh.jpg]]\n| caption                   = \n| birth_date                = 5 December 1977<ref>https://www.mpinfo.org/mpinfostatic/english/council/cabinetmin/Shri-Priyavrat-Singh.asp</ref>\n| birth_place               = [[Indore]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| residence                 = [[Khilchipur]]\n| nationality               = [[Indian]]\n| citizenship               = [[India]]\n| office1                   = [[Kamal Nath ministry|Cabinet Minister ]]<br>[[Government of Madhya Pradesh]]\n| party                     = [[Indian National Congress]]\n}}\n\n\n'''Priyavrat Singh''' (born 5 December 1977 ) is an Indian politician who served as a member of [[Indian National Congress]] as the [[Member Of Legislative Assembly|Member of Legislative Assembly]] of [[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly|Madhya Pradhesh]] in 2003 and was re-elected in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elections.in/madhya-pradesh/assembly-constituencies/2008-election-results.html|title=Madhya Pradesh Assembly Election Results in 2008|website=www.elections.in|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> He served the constituency of [[Khilchipur (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Khilchipur Vidhan Sabha]] and was a  [[Cabinet minister]] of MP Govt. He is also Known as Raja of [[Khilchipur]].<ref>http://www.indianrajputs.com/view/khilchipur</ref>\n\n==Political Career==\nHe served as a Cabinet Minister in the [[Kamal Nath ministry|'''Kamal Nath ministry''']] of Madhya Pradesh Government, between December 2018 and March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mpinfo.org/mpinfostatic/english/council/cabinetmin/Shri-Priyavrat-Singh.asp|title=::Department Of Public Relations,Madhya Pradesh::|website=www.mpinfo.org|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians from Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Indore]]\n[[Category:Madhya Pradesh MLAs 2008\u20132013]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n\n{{India-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Indsoft", "label": "safe", "comment": "Image link and infobox creation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Priyavrat_Singh"}
{"title_page": "Sweating sickness", "text_new": "{{About||the benign condition characterized by abnormally increased perspiration|Hyperhidrosis|the tick-borne disease of cattle in Africa|Sweating sickness (cattle)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Sweating sickness\n| synonyms        = English sweating sickness, English sweat, (Latin) sudor anglicus\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''Sweating sickness''', also known as '''English sweating sickness''' or '''English sweat''' or (Latin) '''sudor anglicus''', was a mysterious and contagious disease that struck England and later continental Europe in a series of epidemics beginning in 1485. The last outbreak occurred in 1551, after which the disease apparently vanished. The onset of symptoms was sudden, with death often occurring within hours. Its cause remains unknown, although it has been suggested that an unknown species of [[hantavirus pulmonary syndrome|hantavirus]] was responsible.\n\n== Signs and symptoms ==\n[[John Caius]] was a practising physician in Shrewsbury in 1551, when an outbreak occurred, and he described the symptoms and signs of the disease in ''A Boke or Counseill Against the Disease Commonly Called the Sweate, or Sweatyng Sicknesse'' (1552), which is the main historical source of knowledge of the disease. It began very suddenly with a sense of apprehension, followed by cold shivers (sometimes very violent), giddiness, headache, and severe pains in the neck, shoulders, and limbs, with great exhaustion. The cold stage might last from half an hour to three hours, after which the hot and sweating stage began. The characteristic sweat broke out suddenly without any obvious cause. A sense of heat, headache, [[delirium]], rapid pulse, and intense thirst accompanied the sweat. Palpitation and pain in the heart were frequent symptoms, as well. No skin eruptions were noted by observers, including Caius.  In the final stages, there was either general exhaustion and collapse, or an irresistible urge to sleep, which Caius thought was fatal if the patient were permitted to give way to it. One attack did not produce immunity, and some people suffered several bouts before dying.<ref name=Heyman2014>{{cite journal|authors=Heyman P. & Simons L. & Cochez, C. |title=Were the English Sweating Sickness and the Picardy Sweat Caused by Hantaviruses?|journal= Viruses|date= 2014|volume=6|number=1|pages=151\u2013171|doi=10.3390/v6010151|pmid=24402305 |pmc=3917436}}</ref> The disease tended to occur in summer and early autumn.\n\n== Cause ==\nThe cause is the most mysterious aspect of the disease. Commentators then and now put much blame on the sewage, generally poor sanitation, and contaminated water supplies of the time, which might have harboured the source of infection. The first confirmed outbreak was in August 1485 at the end of the [[Wars of the Roses]], which has led to speculation that it may have been brought over from France by the French mercenaries whom [[Henry VII of England|Henry Tudor]] used to gain the English throne.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Theilmann |first1=John M. |editor1-last=Byrnes |editor1-first=Joseph P. |title=Encyclopedia of pestilence, pandemics, and plagues |date=2008 |publisher=Greenwood Press |isbn=978-0313341014 |page=686, \"Sweating Sickness\" |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fg5hDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA686}}</ref> However, an earlier outbreak may have affected the city of York in June 1485, before Tudor's army landed, although the record of that disease's symptoms is not adequate to be certain.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Petre |first1=James |title=Richard III crown and people |date=1985 |publisher=Sutton Publishing Ltd |isbn=978-0904893113 |page=383 |quote=A 'plage of pestilence' was known in York as early as June 1485, but no symptoms were described, and we cannot tell what gave [Sir Thomas] Stanley the idea to cite the sweating sickness.}}</ref> Regardless, the ''[[Croyland Chronicle]]'' mentions that [[Thomas Stanley, 1st Earl of Derby]] used the sweating sickness as an excuse not to join with [[Richard III of England|Richard III]]'s army prior to Tudor's victory over Richard at the [[Battle of Bosworth]].<ref name=Heyman2014/>\n\n[[Relapsing fever]] has been proposed as a possible cause. This disease is spread by ticks and lice, and it occurs most often during the summer months, as did the original sweating sickness. However, relapsing fever is marked by a prominent black scab at the site of the tick bite and a subsequent skin rash.\n\nSeveral researchers have noted that symptoms overlap with [[hantavirus pulmonary syndrome]] and have proposed an unknown [[hantavirus]] as the cause.<ref name=Heyman2014/><ref>{{Cite journal|pmid=9023099|year=1997|last1=Thwaites|first1=G|last2=Taviner|first2=M|last3=Gant|first3=V|title=The English sweating sickness, 1485 to 1551|volume=336|issue=8|pages=580\u20132|doi=10.1056/NEJM199702203360812|journal=The New England Journal of Medicine}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|pmc=1043971|year=1998|last1=Taviner|first1=M|last2=Thwaites|first2=G|last3=Gant|first3=V|title=The English sweating sickness, 1485-1551: A viral pulmonary disease?|volume=42|issue=1|pages=96\u201398|journal=Medical History|doi=10.1017/S0025727300063365|pmid=9536626}}</ref> A critique of this hypothesis argued that sweating sickness was thought to be transmitted from human to human, whereas hantaviruses are rarely spread that way.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3874/is_200101/ai_n8939673  |title=English 'sweate' (Sudor Anglicus) and Hantavirus pulmonary syndrome, The |publisher=British Journal of Biomedical Science |year=2001 |last=Bridson |first= Eric}}</ref> However, infection via human contact has been suggested in hantavirus outbreaks in Argentina.<ref name=\"Padula\">{{cite journal|last1=Padula|first1=P|last2=Edelstein|first2=A|last3=Miguel|first3=SD|last4=L\u00f3pez|first4=NM|last5=Rossi|first5=CM|last6=Rabinovich |first6=RD|date=15 February 1998|title=Hantavirus pulmonary syndrome outbreak in Argentina: molecular evidence for person-to-person transmission of Andes virus|journal=Virology|publisher=Elsevier|location=London|volume=241|issue=2|pages=323\u2013330|doi=10.1006/viro.1997.8976|pmid=9499807}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, microbiologist Edward McSweegan suggested that the disease may have been an outbreak of [[anthrax]] poisoning. He hypothesized that the victims could have been infected with anthrax spores present in raw wool or infected animal carcasses, and he suggested exhuming the victims for testing.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg18124302.400-riddle-solved.html |title=Riddle solved? |date=17 January 2004 |journal=New Scientist|author=McSweegan, Edward}}</ref>\n\n== Epidemiology ==\n[[File:Arthur Prince of Wales c 1500.jpg|thumb|[[Arthur, Prince of Wales]], who may have died of the sweating sickness in 1502]]\n[[File:Hans Holbein the Younger - Henry Brandon, 2nd Duke of Suffolk (1535-51) - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|[[Henry Brandon, 2nd Duke of Suffolk]], who in 1551 died of the sweating sickness hours before his brother Charles]]\n[[File:Hans Holbein the Younger - Charles Brandon (Royal Collection).JPG|thumb|[[Charles Brandon, 3rd Duke of Suffolk]], died of the sweating sickness]]\n\n===15th century===\nSweating sickness first came to the attention of physicians at the beginning of the reign of Henry VII, in 1485. There is no definitive statement that the sickness was present in troops landing at [[Milford Haven]]. Henry arrived in London on 28 August soon after the Battle of Bosworth, and the disease broke out on 19 September 1485;<ref name=Roberts>{{cite journal|pmc=2059547|year=1945|last1=Roberts|first1=L|title=Sweating Sickness and Picardy Sweat|journal=British Medical Journal|volume=2|issue=4414|pages=196|doi=10.1136/bmj.2.4414.196}}</ref> it had killed several thousand people by its conclusion in late October that year.<ref>{{cite book | first=John | last=Entick | authorlink=John Entick | year=1766 | title=A new and accurate history and survey of London, Westminster, Southwark, and places adjacent | url=https://archive.org/details/anewandaccurate03entigoog | location=London | pages=[https://archive.org/details/anewandaccurate03entigoog/page/n438 434], vol. 1 }}</ref> Among those killed were two lord mayors, six aldermen, and three sheriffs.<ref>{{cite book | first=Walter | last=Harrison | year=1775 | title=A new and universal history, description and survey of the cities of London and Westminster, the borough of Southwark | location=London | page=127 }}</ref>\n\nThis alarming malady soon became known as the sweating sickness. It was regarded as being quite distinct from the [[Black Death]], the pestilential fever, or other epidemics previously known because of the sweating which gave it its name and its extremely rapid and fatal course. It reached Ireland in 1492, when the ''[[Annals of Ulster]]'' record the death of [[James Fleming, 7th Baron Slane]] from the ''pl\u00e1igh allais'', newly come to Ireland.<ref>''[[Annals of Ulster]]'' vol.iii, ed. B. MacCarthy, Dublin, 1895, pp 358f.</ref> The ''[[Annals of Connacht]]'' also record this obituary,<ref>Annals of Connacht'' ed. A. M. Freeman, Dublin, 1944, pp 594f.</ref> and the ''[[Annals of the Four Masters]]'' record \"an unusual plague in Meath\" of 24 hours' duration;<ref>''Annals of the Four Masters'' vol.iii, ed. J. O'Donovan, Dublin, 1856, pp 1194f.</ref> people recovered if they survived it beyond that 24-hour period. It did not attack infants or little children. However, Freeman denies that this \"plague\" was the sweating sickness, despite the similarity of the names. He thought it to be \"Relapsing or Famine Fever\"\u2014possibly [[typhus]].\n\n===16th century===\n[[File:Euricius cordus - englisch schweiss.jpg|thumb|Title of a publication in [[Marburg]], 1529, about the English Sweating sickness]]\nNothing was recorded of the ailment from 1492 to 1502. It may have been the condition which afflicted [[Arthur, Prince of Wales]] (the elder brother of [[Henry VIII of England]]) and his wife [[Catherine of Aragon]] in March 1502; their illness was described as \"a malign vapour which proceeded from the air\".<ref>{{cite book | title=The Six Wives of Henry VIII | publisher=Grove Press | last=Weir | first=Alison | year=2007 | location=New York | isbn=978-0-8021-3683-1 | p=[https://archive.org/details/sixwivesofhenryv00weir_1/page/37 37] | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/sixwivesofhenryv00weir_1 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=The Virgin Queen: A Personal History of Elizabeth I | publisher=Viking Press | last=Hibbert | first=Christopher | year=2010 | location=New York | isbn=978-1-84885-555-7 | p=4}}</ref> Other suggestions include [[tuberculosis]] (\"consumption\"),<ref>{{cite book | title=Mary Tudor: England's First Queen | publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing | last=Whitelock | first=Anna | year=2010 | location=London | isbn=978-1-4088-0078-2 | p=[https://archive.org/details/marytudorengland0000whit/page/14 14] | url=https://archive.org/details/marytudorengland0000whit/page/14 }}</ref> the [[Black Death]],<ref>{{cite book | title=Westminster Abbey: The Lady Chapel of Henry VII | publisher=Boydell Press | last1=Tatton-Brown | first1=T.W.T. | last2=Mortimer | first2=Richard | year=2003 | location=Woodbridge | isbn=1-84383-037-X | p=286}}</ref> and [[influenza]].<ref>{{cite book | title=Journey to Avalon: The Final Discovery of King Arthur | publisher=Weiser Books | last1=Barber | first1=Chris | last2=Pykitt | first2=David | year=1997 | location=York Beach, ME | isbn=1-57863-024-X | p=269}}</ref>\n\nResearchers opened Arthur's tomb in 2002 but could not determine the exact cause of death. One possible cause was a genetic ailment which also affected Arthur's nephew [[Edward VI of England|Edward VI]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1394759/Discovery-of-grave-may-solve-mystery-death-of-Henry-VIIIs-brother-at-15.html | title=Discovery of grave may solve mystery death of Henry VIII's brother at 15| work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | date=20 May 2002 | accessdate=31 December 2015| author=Derbyshire, David}}</ref> Catherine recovered, but Arthur died on 2 April 1502 in his home at [[Ludlow Castle]], six months short of his sixteenth birthday.<ref>{{cite book | title=Henry VIII | publisher=Oxford University Press | last=Ives | first=Eric | year=2007 | location=Oxford | isbn=978-0-19-921759-5 | p=1}}</ref>\n\nA less widespread outbreak occurred in 1507, followed by a third and much more severe epidemic later that year which also spread to [[Calais]].<ref name=Roberts/> It was frequently fatal; half the population perished in some areas. It reached epidemic proportions in 1528 during its fourth outbreak. It first broke out in London at the end of May and speedily spread over the whole of England, save the far north. It did not spread to Scotland, though it did reach Ireland where Lord Chancellor [[Hugh Inge]] was the most prominent victim.<ref name=\"Ball2005\">{{cite book|first=F. Elrington|last=Ball|authorlink=F. Elrington Ball|title=The Judges in Ireland, 1221\u20131921|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rqeSXWqKAD8C&pg=PA117|accessdate=5 May 2011|date=September 2005|origyear=First published 1926|publisher=The Lawbook Exchange|isbn=978-1-58477-428-0|pages=117\u2013}}</ref> The mortality rate was very high in London; Henry VIII broke up the court and left London, frequently changing his residence.\n\nThe disease suddenly appeared in Hamburg, spreading so rapidly that more than a thousand people died in a few weeks. It swept through eastern Europe as an epidemic causing high mortality rates. It arrived in Switzerland in December, then was carried northwards to Denmark, Sweden, and Norway, and eastwards to Lithuania, Poland, and Russia. Cases of the disease were not known to occur in Italy or France, except in the [[Pale of Calais]] which was controlled by England at the time. It also emerged in Flanders and the Netherlands,<ref name=Roberts/> possibly transmitted directly from England by travelers; it appeared simultaneously in the cities of Antwerp and Amsterdam on the morning of 27 September. In each place, it prevailed for a short time, generally not more than two weeks. By the end of the year, it had entirely disappeared except in eastern Switzerland, where it lingered into the next year. After this, the disease did not recur on mainland Europe.\n\n===Final outbreak===\nThe last major outbreak of the disease occurred in England in 1551.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=The English Sweating Sickness, with Particular Reference to the 1551 Outbreak in Chester|author=Hunter, Paul R.|year=1991|journal=Reviews of Infectious Diseases|volume=13|issue=2|pages=303\u2013306|jstor = 4455857|doi = 10.1093/clinids/13.2.303|pmid = 2041963}}</ref> [[John Caius]] wrote ''A Boke or Counseill Against the Disease Commonly Called the Sweate, or Sweatyng Sicknesse'' as an eyewitness account. Henry Machin also recorded it in his diary:\n\n{{quote|text=\nthe vii day of July begane a nuw swet in London\u2026the x day of July [1551] the Kynges grace removyd from Westmynster unto Hamtun courte, for ther [died] serten besyd the court, and caused the Kynges grase to be gone so sune, for ther ded in London mony marchants and grett ryche men and women, and yonge men and old, of the new swett\u2026the xvi day of July ded of the swet the ii yonge dukes of Suffoke of the swet, both in one bed in Chambrydge-shyre\u2026and ther ded from the vii day of July unto the xix ded of the swett in London of all dyssesus\u2026 [872] and no more in alle|sign=''The Diary of [[Henry Machyn]] 1550\u20131563''<ref>{{citation|title=The Diary of Henry Machyn 1550\u20131563|date=1848|author=Henry Machin|pages=7\u20138|url=https://archive.org/stream/henrymachyncit00camduoft#page/6/mode/2up}}</ref>|}}\n\nReference is made in the ''Annals'' of [[Halifax, West Yorkshire|Halifax Parish]] in 1551 to an outbreak there, resulting in 44 deaths.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taylor|first=D|title=Annals of the Parish of Halifax|journal=Halifax Antiquarian Society|date=28 March 1972|page=109|quote=1551 44 persons died of the 'sweating Sickness' in the Halifax Parish.}}</ref> A disease outbreak of something called 'sweating sickness' occurred in [[Tiverton, Devon]] in 1644, recorded in Martin Dunsford's History, which led to the deaths of 443 people, 105 of them buried in the month of October.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dunsford|first=Martin|title=Historical memoirs of the town and parish of Tiverton|date=1836|page=36}}</ref> However, there were no medical particulars recorded, and the 1644 date falls well after the generally accepted disappearance of the 'sweating sickness' in 1551.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Creighton |first1=Charles |title=A history of epidemics in Britain |date=1891 |publisher=Cambridge Univ. |page=[https://archive.org/details/historyofepidemi01crei/page/554 554] |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofepidemi01crei |accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Picardy sweat==\nA similar illness occurred in France between 1718 and 1918 known as the [[Picardy sweat]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Foster|first=Michael G.|title=Contributions to Medical & Biological Research|chapter=Sweating Sickness in Modern Times|pages=52\u20133|volume=1|publisher=Paul B. Hoeber|location=New York|date=1919|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/contributionstom01osleuoft|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> Llywelyn Roberts noted \"a great similarity between the two diseases.\"<ref name=Roberts/> It was accompanied by a rash, which was not described as a feature of the English disease. However, Henry Tidy argued that John Caius' report applies to [[fulminant]] cases fatal within a few hours, in which type no eruption may develop. A 1906 outbreak of Picardy sweat struck 6,000 people; bacteriologist [[Andr\u00e9 Chantemesse]] led a commission which studied it, and they attributed infection to the fleas of field mice. Henry Tidy found \"no substantial reason to doubt the identity of ''sudor anglicus'' and Picardy sweat.\"<ref name=Heyman2014/><ref name=Tidy>{{cite journal| pmc=2059374 | pages=63\u201364 | volume=2 | issue=4410 | journal=Br Med J | title=Sweating Sickness and Picardy Sweat | year=945 | doi=10.1136/bmj.2.4410.63-a|last1 = Tidy|first1 = H.}}</ref>\n\n==Popular culture==\n''[[The Tudors]]'' episode \"Message to the Emperor\" (2007), depicts the 1528 outbreak. [[William Compton (The Tudors)|William Compton]] is killed by the disease, and both [[Anne Boleyn]] and [[Cardinal Wolsey]] are stricken. Wolsey actually did survive several attacks of sweating sickness. Henry VIII's illegitimate son [[Henry FitzRoy, 1st Duke of Richmond and Somerset]] dies of the sweat as a young child several episodes prior. A physician treats a mortally afflicted Compton by puncturing his back and bleeding him, on the rumor that it has worked for some by releasing \"the toxin\". The real Henry FitzRoy died about one month after his 17th birthday, probably of [[tuberculosis]],{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} and the real [[William Compton (courtier)|William Compton]] died of sweating sickness at age 46.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nIn [[Hilary Mantel]]'s historical novel ''[[Wolf Hall]]'' (2009), a small outbreak in 1527 kills [[Elizabeth Wyckes|Liz]], the wife of [[Thomas Cromwell]], Cardinal Wolsey's advisor. In 1529, the disease also claims the lives of Cromwell's daughters Grace and Anne. In the eponymous 2015 ''[[Wolf Hall (TV series)|television adaptation]]'' of Mantel's novel, all three die on the same day, in episode 1.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tudor Tales|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2009/10/19/tudor-tales|work=The New Yorker|accessdate=26 April 2015|date=19 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe American science fiction television series ''[[Warehouse 13]]'' features sweating sickness midway through [[Warehouse 13 (season 4)|season 4]]. It is revealed to be an artifact in the form of a Chinese orchid that would release the deadly disease if removed from its container. The events of the story arc suggest that the disease originally vanished from Europe when the orchid was reconstituted into its original form and stored in a previous warehouse.\n\nThe British fantasy-adventure drama television series ''[[Merlin (TV series)|Merlin]]'' features sweating sickness, although the illness historically did not appear until many centuries after any of the supposed dates for the historical [[King Arthur|Arthur]], and none of the [[Arthurian legends|legends surrounding him]] discuss plague outbreaks.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Sweating-Sickness|volume=26|pages=186\u2013187}}\n*{{cite book |title=Life and Writings of Blessed Thomas More, Lord Chancellor of England and Martyr Under Henry VIII.     |last=Bridgett |first=Thomas Edward |year=1904 |location=Original from the University of Wisconsin \u2013 Madison |page=74 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v3xmAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA74&dq=thomas+more+sweating+sickness#PPA74,M1}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal|pmid=11284216|year=2001|last1=Bridson|first1=E|title=The English 'sweate' (Sudor Anglicus) and Hantavirus pulmonary syndrome|journal=British Journal of Biomedical Science|volume=58|issue=1|pages=1\u20136}}\n*{{cite journal|doi=10.1093/jhmas/54.1.23|title=The English Sweating Sickness (1485-c.1551): A New Perspective on Disease Etiology|journal=Journal of the History of Medicine and Allied Sciences|volume=54|pages=23\u201354|year=1999|last1=Carlson|first1=J. R.|last2=Hammond|first2=P. W.}}\n* {{cite journal|pmc=1044802|year=1997|last1=Dyer|first1=A|title=The English sweating sickness of 1551: An epidemic anatomized|journal=Medical History|volume=41|issue=3|pages=362\u2013384|doi=10.1017/s0025727300062724|pmid=9327632}}\n* Flood, John L. \"Englischer Schwei\u00df und deutscher Flei\u00df. Ein Beitrag zur Buchhandelsgeschichte des 16. Jahrhunderts,\" in ''The German book in Wolfenb\u00fcttel and abroad. Studies presented to Ulrich Kopp in his retirement,'' ed. William A. Kelly & J\u00fcrgen Beyer [Studies in reading and book culture 1] (Tartu: University of Tartu Press, 2014), pp.&nbsp;119\u2013178. {{in lang|de}}\n*{{cite journal|doi=10.1056/NEJM199702203360812|pmid=9023099|title=The English Sweating Sickness, 1485 to 1551|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=336|issue=8|pages=580\u20132|year=1997|last1=Thwaites|first1=Guy|last2=Taviner|first2=Mark|last3=Gant|first3=Vanya}}\n*{{cite journal|pmid=7037928|year=1981|last1=Wylie|first1=J. A.|title=The English Sweating sickness (sudor Anglicus): A reappraisal|journal=Journal of the History of Medicine and Allied Sciences|volume=36|issue=4|pages=425\u201345|last2=Collier|first2=L. H.|doi=10.1093/jhmas/xxxvi.4.425}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB     =\n| ICD10          =\n| ICD9           = {{ICD9|078.2}}\n| ICDO           =\n| OMIM           =\n| MedlinePlus    =\n| eMedicineSubj  =\n| eMedicineTopic =\n| MeshID         = D018614\n}}\n* [http://www.abc.net.au/rn/ockhamsrazor/stories/2007/2039403.htm ''Sweating Fever''] Jim Leavesley commemorates the 500th anniversary of the first outbreak \u2013 transcript of talk on ''Ockham's Razor'' ABC [[Radio National]]\n*[http://www.csuchico.edu/geop/Flash%20Gallery/Pittman.swf The Curious Case of the English Sweating Sickness], contains a map of the disease dispersion created and mapped by Kirstyn Pittman from [[California State University, Chico]] (requires [[Adobe Flash]])\n*[http://discovermagazine.com/1997/jun/thesweatingsickn1161 \"The Sweating Sickness Returns\", ''Discover Magazine'', 1 June 1997]\n\n{{Viral diseases}}\n{{Epidemics}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sweating Sickness}}\n[[Category:1485 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:1551 disestablishments in England]]\n[[Category:15th-century epidemics]]\n[[Category:16th-century epidemics]]\n[[Category:1485 in Europe]]\n[[Category:1507 in Europe]]\n[[Category:1517 in Europe]]\n[[Category:1528 in Europe]]\n[[Category:1551 in Europe]]\n[[Category:1485 in England]]\n[[Category:1517 in England]]\n[[Category:1528 in England]]\n[[Category:1551 in England]]\n[[Category:Ailments of unknown cause]]\n[[Category:Retrospective diagnosis]]\n[[Category:History of medicine]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the benign condition characterized by abnormally increased perspiration|Hyperhidrosis|the tick-borne disease of cattle in Africa|Sweating sickness (cattle)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Sweating sickness\n| synonyms        = English sweating sickness, English sweat, (Latin) sudor anglicus\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''Sweating sickness''', also known as '''English sweating sickness''' or '''English sweat''' or (Latin) '''sudor anglicus''', was a mysterious and contagious disease that struck England and later continental Europe in a series of epidemics beginning in 1485. The last outbreak occurred in 1551, after which the disease apparently vanished. The onset of symptoms was sudden, with death often occurring within hours. Its cause remains unknown, although it has been suggested that an unknown species of [[hantavirus pulmonary syndrome|hantavirus]] was responsible.\n\n== Signs and symptoms ==\n[[John Caius]] was a practising physician in Shrewsbury in 1551, when an outbreak occurred, and he described the symptoms and signs of the disease in ''A Boke or Counseill Against the Disease Commonly Called the Sweate, or Sweatyng Sicknesse'' (1552), which is the main historical source of knowledge of the disease. It began very suddenly with a sense of apprehension, followed by cold shivers (sometimes very violent), giddiness, headache, and severe pains in the neck, shoulders, and limbs, with great exhaustion. The cold stage might last from half an hour to three hours, after which the hot and sweating stage began. The characteristic sweat broke out suddenly without any obvious cause. A sense of heat, headache, [[delirium]], rapid pulse, and intense thirst accompanied the sweat. Palpitation and pain in the heart were frequent symptoms, as well. No skin eruptions were noted by observers, including Caius.  In the final stages, there was either general exhaustion and collapse, or an irresistible urge to sleep, which Caius thought was fatal if the patient were permitted to give way to it. One attack did not produce immunity, and some people suffered several bouts before dying.<ref name=Heyman2014>{{cite journal|authors=Heyman P. & Simons L. & Cochez, C. |title=Were the English Sweating Sickness and the Picardy Sweat Caused by Hantaviruses?|journal= Viruses|date= 2014|volume=6|number=1|pages=151\u2013171|doi=10.3390/v6010151|pmid=24402305 |pmc=3917436}}</ref> The disease tended to occur in summer and early autumn.\n\n== Cause ==\nThe cause is the most mysterious aspect of the disease. Commentators then and now put much blame on the sewage, generally poor sanitation, and contaminated water supplies of the time, which might have harboured the source of infection. The first confirmed outbreak was in August 1485 at the end of the [[Wars of the Roses]], which has led to speculation that it may have been brought over from France by the French mercenaries whom [[Henry VII of England|Henry Tudor]] used to gain the English throne.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Theilmann |first1=John M. |editor1-last=Byrnes |editor1-first=Joseph P. |title=Encyclopedia of pestilence, pandemics, and plagues |date=2008 |publisher=Greenwood Press |isbn=978-0313341014 |page=686, \"Sweating Sickness\" |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fg5hDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA686}}</ref> However, an earlier outbreak may have affected the city of York in June 1485, before Tudor's army landed, although the record of that disease's symptoms is not adequate to be certain.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Petre |first1=James |title=Richard III crown and people |date=1985 |publisher=Sutton Publishing Ltd |isbn=978-0904893113 |page=383 |quote=A 'plage of pestilence' was known in York as early as June 1485, but no symptoms were described, and we cannot tell what gave [Sir Thomas] Stanley the idea to cite the sweating sickness.}}</ref> Regardless, the ''[[Croyland Chronicle]]'' mentions that [[Thomas Stanley, 1st Earl of Derby]] used the sweating sickness as an excuse not to join with [[Richard III of England|Richard III]]'s army prior to Tudor's victory over Richard at the [[Battle of Bosworth]].<ref name=Heyman2014/>\n\n[[Relapsing fever]] has been proposed as a possible cause. This disease is spread by ticks and lice, and it occurs most often during the summer months, as did the original sweating sickness. However, relapsing fever is marked by a prominent black scab at the site of the tick bite and a subsequent skin rash.\n\nSeveral researchers have noted that symptoms overlap with [[hantavirus pulmonary syndrome]] and have proposed an unknown [[hantavirus]] as the cause.<ref name=Heyman2014/><ref>{{Cite journal|pmid=9023099|year=1997|last1=Thwaites|first1=G|last2=Taviner|first2=M|last3=Gant|first3=V|title=The English sweating sickness, 1485 to 1551|volume=336|issue=8|pages=580\u20132|doi=10.1056/NEJM199702203360812|journal=The New England Journal of Medicine}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|pmc=1043971|year=1998|last1=Taviner|first1=M|last2=Thwaites|first2=G|last3=Gant|first3=V|title=The English sweating sickness, 1485-1551: A viral pulmonary disease?|volume=42|issue=1|pages=96\u201398|journal=Medical History|doi=10.1017/S0025727300063365|pmid=9536626}}</ref> A critique of this hypothesis argued that sweating sickness was thought to be transmitted from human to human, whereas hantaviruses are rarely spread that way.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3874/is_200101/ai_n8939673  |title=English 'sweate' (Sudor Anglicus) and Hantavirus pulmonary syndrome, The |publisher=British Journal of Biomedical Science |year=2001 |last=Bridson |first= Eric}}</ref> However, infection via human contact has been suggested in hantavirus outbreaks in Argentina.<ref name=\"Padula\">{{cite journal|last1=Padula|first1=P|last2=Edelstein|first2=A|last3=Miguel|first3=SD|last4=L\u00f3pez|first4=NM|last5=Rossi|first5=CM|last6=Rabinovich |first6=RD|date=15 February 1998|title=Hantavirus pulmonary syndrome outbreak in Argentina: molecular evidence for person-to-person transmission of Andes virus|journal=Virology|publisher=Elsevier|location=London|volume=241|issue=2|pages=323\u2013330|doi=10.1006/viro.1997.8976|pmid=9499807}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, microbiologist Edward McSweegan suggested that the disease may have been an outbreak of [[anthrax]] poisoning. He hypothesized that the victims could have been infected with anthrax spores present in raw wool or infected animal carcasses, and he suggested exhuming the victims for testing.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg18124302.400-riddle-solved.html |title=Riddle solved? |date=17 January 2004 |journal=New Scientist|author=McSweegan, Edward}}</ref>\n\n== Epidemiology ==\n[[File:Arthur Prince of Wales c 1500.jpg|thumb|[[Arthur, Prince of Wales]], who may have died of the sweating sickness in 1502]]\n[[File:Hans Holbein the Younger - Henry Brandon, 2nd Duke of Suffolk (1535-51) - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|[[Henry Brandon, 2nd Duke of Suffolk]], who in 1551 died of the sweating sickness hours before his brother Charles]]\n[[File:Hans Holbein the Younger - Charles Brandon (Royal Collection).JPG|thumb|[[Charles Brandon, 3rd Duke of Suffolk]], died of the sweating sickness]]\n\n===15th century===\nSweating sickness first came to the attention of physicians at the beginning of the reign of Henry VII, in 1485. There is no definitive statement that the sickness was present in troops landing at [[Milford Haven]]. Henry arrived in London on 28 August soon after the Battle of Bosworth, and the disease broke out on 19 September 1485;<ref name=Roberts>{{cite journal|pmc=2059547|year=1945|last1=Roberts|first1=L|title=Sweating Sickness and Picardy Sweat|journal=British Medical Journal|volume=2|issue=4414|pages=196|doi=10.1136/bmj.2.4414.196}}</ref> it had killed several thousand people by its conclusion in late October that year.<ref>{{cite book | first=John | last=Entick | authorlink=John Entick | year=1766 | title=A new and accurate history and survey of London, Westminster, Southwark, and places adjacent | url=https://archive.org/details/anewandaccurate03entigoog | location=London | pages=[https://archive.org/details/anewandaccurate03entigoog/page/n438 434], vol. 1 }}</ref> Among those killed were two lords mayor, six aldermen, and three sheriffs.<ref>{{cite book | first=Walter | last=Harrison | year=1775 | title=A new and universal history, description and survey of the cities of London and Westminster, the borough of Southwark | location=London | page=127 }}</ref>\n\nThis alarming malady soon became known as the sweating sickness. It was regarded as being quite distinct from the [[Black Death]], the pestilential fever, or other epidemics previously known because of the sweating which gave it its name and its extremely rapid and fatal course. It reached Ireland in 1492, when the ''[[Annals of Ulster]]'' record the death of [[James Fleming, 7th Baron Slane]] from the ''pl\u00e1igh allais'', newly come to Ireland.<ref>''[[Annals of Ulster]]'' vol.iii, ed. B. MacCarthy, Dublin, 1895, pp 358f.</ref> The ''[[Annals of Connacht]]'' also record this obituary,<ref>Annals of Connacht'' ed. A. M. Freeman, Dublin, 1944, pp 594f.</ref> and the ''[[Annals of the Four Masters]]'' record \"an unusual plague in Meath\" of 24 hours' duration;<ref>''Annals of the Four Masters'' vol.iii, ed. J. O'Donovan, Dublin, 1856, pp 1194f.</ref> people recovered if they survived it beyond that 24-hour period. It did not attack infants or little children. However, Freeman denies that this \"plague\" was the sweating sickness, despite the similarity of the names. He thought it to be \"Relapsing or Famine Fever\"\u2014possibly [[typhus]].\n\n===16th century===\n[[File:Euricius cordus - englisch schweiss.jpg|thumb|Title of a publication in [[Marburg]], 1529, about the English Sweating sickness]]\nNothing was recorded of the ailment from 1492 to 1502. It may have been the condition which afflicted [[Arthur, Prince of Wales]] (the elder brother of [[Henry VIII of England]]) and his wife [[Catherine of Aragon]] in March 1502; their illness was described as \"a malign vapour which proceeded from the air\".<ref>{{cite book | title=The Six Wives of Henry VIII | publisher=Grove Press | last=Weir | first=Alison | year=2007 | location=New York | isbn=978-0-8021-3683-1 | p=[https://archive.org/details/sixwivesofhenryv00weir_1/page/37 37] | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/sixwivesofhenryv00weir_1 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=The Virgin Queen: A Personal History of Elizabeth I | publisher=Viking Press | last=Hibbert | first=Christopher | year=2010 | location=New York | isbn=978-1-84885-555-7 | p=4}}</ref> Other suggestions include [[tuberculosis]] (\"consumption\"),<ref>{{cite book | title=Mary Tudor: England's First Queen | publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing | last=Whitelock | first=Anna | year=2010 | location=London | isbn=978-1-4088-0078-2 | p=[https://archive.org/details/marytudorengland0000whit/page/14 14] | url=https://archive.org/details/marytudorengland0000whit/page/14 }}</ref> the [[Black Death]],<ref>{{cite book | title=Westminster Abbey: The Lady Chapel of Henry VII | publisher=Boydell Press | last1=Tatton-Brown | first1=T.W.T. | last2=Mortimer | first2=Richard | year=2003 | location=Woodbridge | isbn=1-84383-037-X | p=286}}</ref> and [[influenza]].<ref>{{cite book | title=Journey to Avalon: The Final Discovery of King Arthur | publisher=Weiser Books | last1=Barber | first1=Chris | last2=Pykitt | first2=David | year=1997 | location=York Beach, ME | isbn=1-57863-024-X | p=269}}</ref>\n\nResearchers opened Arthur's tomb in 2002 but could not determine the exact cause of death. One possible cause was a genetic ailment which also affected Arthur's nephew [[Edward VI of England|Edward VI]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1394759/Discovery-of-grave-may-solve-mystery-death-of-Henry-VIIIs-brother-at-15.html | title=Discovery of grave may solve mystery death of Henry VIII's brother at 15| work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | date=20 May 2002 | accessdate=31 December 2015| author=Derbyshire, David}}</ref> Catherine recovered, but Arthur died on 2 April 1502 in his home at [[Ludlow Castle]], six months short of his sixteenth birthday.<ref>{{cite book | title=Henry VIII | publisher=Oxford University Press | last=Ives | first=Eric | year=2007 | location=Oxford | isbn=978-0-19-921759-5 | p=1}}</ref>\n\nA less widespread outbreak occurred in 1507, followed by a third and much more severe epidemic later that year which also spread to [[Calais]].<ref name=Roberts/> It was frequently fatal; half the population perished in some areas. It reached epidemic proportions in 1528 during its fourth outbreak. It first broke out in London at the end of May and speedily spread over the whole of England, save the far north. It did not spread to Scotland, though it did reach Ireland where Lord Chancellor [[Hugh Inge]] was the most prominent victim.<ref name=\"Ball2005\">{{cite book|first=F. Elrington|last=Ball|authorlink=F. Elrington Ball|title=The Judges in Ireland, 1221\u20131921|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rqeSXWqKAD8C&pg=PA117|accessdate=5 May 2011|date=September 2005|origyear=First published 1926|publisher=The Lawbook Exchange|isbn=978-1-58477-428-0|pages=117\u2013}}</ref> The mortality rate was very high in London; Henry VIII broke up the court and left London, frequently changing his residence.\n\nThe disease suddenly appeared in Hamburg, spreading so rapidly that more than a thousand people died in a few weeks. It swept through eastern Europe as an epidemic causing high mortality rates. It arrived in Switzerland in December, then was carried northwards to Denmark, Sweden, and Norway, and eastwards to Lithuania, Poland, and Russia. Cases of the disease were not known to occur in Italy or France, except in the [[Pale of Calais]] which was controlled by England at the time. It also emerged in Flanders and the Netherlands,<ref name=Roberts/> possibly transmitted directly from England by travelers; it appeared simultaneously in the cities of Antwerp and Amsterdam on the morning of 27 September. In each place, it prevailed for a short time, generally not more than two weeks. By the end of the year, it had entirely disappeared except in eastern Switzerland, where it lingered into the next year. After this, the disease did not recur on mainland Europe.\n\n===Final outbreak===\nThe last major outbreak of the disease occurred in England in 1551.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=The English Sweating Sickness, with Particular Reference to the 1551 Outbreak in Chester|author=Hunter, Paul R.|year=1991|journal=Reviews of Infectious Diseases|volume=13|issue=2|pages=303\u2013306|jstor = 4455857|doi = 10.1093/clinids/13.2.303|pmid = 2041963}}</ref> [[John Caius]] wrote ''A Boke or Counseill Against the Disease Commonly Called the Sweate, or Sweatyng Sicknesse'' as an eyewitness account. Henry Machin also recorded it in his diary:\n\n{{quote|text=\nthe vii day of July begane a nuw swet in London\u2026the x day of July [1551] the Kynges grace removyd from Westmynster unto Hamtun courte, for ther [died] serten besyd the court, and caused the Kynges grase to be gone so sune, for ther ded in London mony marchants and grett ryche men and women, and yonge men and old, of the new swett\u2026the xvi day of July ded of the swet the ii yonge dukes of Suffoke of the swet, both in one bed in Chambrydge-shyre\u2026and ther ded from the vii day of July unto the xix ded of the swett in London of all dyssesus\u2026 [872] and no more in alle|sign=''The Diary of [[Henry Machyn]] 1550\u20131563''<ref>{{citation|title=The Diary of Henry Machyn 1550\u20131563|date=1848|author=Henry Machin|pages=7\u20138|url=https://archive.org/stream/henrymachyncit00camduoft#page/6/mode/2up}}</ref>|}}\n\nReference is made in the ''Annals'' of [[Halifax, West Yorkshire|Halifax Parish]] in 1551 to an outbreak there, resulting in 44 deaths.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taylor|first=D|title=Annals of the Parish of Halifax|journal=Halifax Antiquarian Society|date=28 March 1972|page=109|quote=1551 44 persons died of the 'sweating Sickness' in the Halifax Parish.}}</ref> A disease outbreak of something called 'sweating sickness' occurred in [[Tiverton, Devon]] in 1644, recorded in Martin Dunsford's History, which led to the deaths of 443 people, 105 of them buried in the month of October.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dunsford|first=Martin|title=Historical memoirs of the town and parish of Tiverton|date=1836|page=36}}</ref> However, there were no medical particulars recorded, and the 1644 date falls well after the generally accepted disappearance of the 'sweating sickness' in 1551.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Creighton |first1=Charles |title=A history of epidemics in Britain |date=1891 |publisher=Cambridge Univ. |page=[https://archive.org/details/historyofepidemi01crei/page/554 554] |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofepidemi01crei |accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Picardy sweat==\nA similar illness occurred in France between 1718 and 1918 known as the [[Picardy sweat]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Foster|first=Michael G.|title=Contributions to Medical & Biological Research|chapter=Sweating Sickness in Modern Times|pages=52\u20133|volume=1|publisher=Paul B. Hoeber|location=New York|date=1919|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/contributionstom01osleuoft|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> Llywelyn Roberts noted \"a great similarity between the two diseases.\"<ref name=Roberts/> It was accompanied by a rash, which was not described as a feature of the English disease. However, Henry Tidy argued that John Caius' report applies to [[fulminant]] cases fatal within a few hours, in which type no eruption may develop. A 1906 outbreak of Picardy sweat struck 6,000 people; bacteriologist [[Andr\u00e9 Chantemesse]] led a commission which studied it, and they attributed infection to the fleas of field mice. Henry Tidy found \"no substantial reason to doubt the identity of ''sudor anglicus'' and Picardy sweat.\"<ref name=Heyman2014/><ref name=Tidy>{{cite journal| pmc=2059374 | pages=63\u201364 | volume=2 | issue=4410 | journal=Br Med J | title=Sweating Sickness and Picardy Sweat | year=945 | doi=10.1136/bmj.2.4410.63-a|last1 = Tidy|first1 = H.}}</ref>\n\n==Popular culture==\n''[[The Tudors]]'' episode \"Message to the Emperor\" (2007), depicts the 1528 outbreak. [[William Compton (The Tudors)|William Compton]] is killed by the disease, and both [[Anne Boleyn]] and [[Cardinal Wolsey]] are stricken. Wolsey actually did survive several attacks of sweating sickness. Henry VIII's illegitimate son [[Henry FitzRoy, 1st Duke of Richmond and Somerset]] dies of the sweat as a young child several episodes prior. A physician treats a mortally afflicted Compton by puncturing his back and bleeding him, on the rumor that it has worked for some by releasing \"the toxin\". The real Henry FitzRoy died about one month after his 17th birthday, probably of [[tuberculosis]],{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} and the real [[William Compton (courtier)|William Compton]] died of sweating sickness at age 46.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nIn [[Hilary Mantel]]'s historical novel ''[[Wolf Hall]]'' (2009), a small outbreak in 1527 kills [[Elizabeth Wyckes|Liz]], the wife of [[Thomas Cromwell]], Cardinal Wolsey's advisor. In 1529, the disease also claims the lives of Cromwell's daughters Grace and Anne. In the eponymous 2015 ''[[Wolf Hall (TV series)|television adaptation]]'' of Mantel's novel, all three die on the same day, in episode 1.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tudor Tales|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2009/10/19/tudor-tales|work=The New Yorker|accessdate=26 April 2015|date=19 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe American science fiction television series ''[[Warehouse 13]]'' features sweating sickness midway through [[Warehouse 13 (season 4)|season 4]]. It is revealed to be an artifact in the form of a Chinese orchid that would release the deadly disease if removed from its container. The events of the story arc suggest that the disease originally vanished from Europe when the orchid was reconstituted into its original form and stored in a previous warehouse.\n\nThe British fantasy-adventure drama television series ''[[Merlin (TV series)|Merlin]]'' features sweating sickness, although the illness historically did not appear until many centuries after any of the supposed dates for the historical [[King Arthur|Arthur]], and none of the [[Arthurian legends|legends surrounding him]] discuss plague outbreaks.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Sweating-Sickness|volume=26|pages=186\u2013187}}\n*{{cite book |title=Life and Writings of Blessed Thomas More, Lord Chancellor of England and Martyr Under Henry VIII.     |last=Bridgett |first=Thomas Edward |year=1904 |location=Original from the University of Wisconsin \u2013 Madison |page=74 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v3xmAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA74&dq=thomas+more+sweating+sickness#PPA74,M1}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal|pmid=11284216|year=2001|last1=Bridson|first1=E|title=The English 'sweate' (Sudor Anglicus) and Hantavirus pulmonary syndrome|journal=British Journal of Biomedical Science|volume=58|issue=1|pages=1\u20136}}\n*{{cite journal|doi=10.1093/jhmas/54.1.23|title=The English Sweating Sickness (1485-c.1551): A New Perspective on Disease Etiology|journal=Journal of the History of Medicine and Allied Sciences|volume=54|pages=23\u201354|year=1999|last1=Carlson|first1=J. R.|last2=Hammond|first2=P. W.}}\n* {{cite journal|pmc=1044802|year=1997|last1=Dyer|first1=A|title=The English sweating sickness of 1551: An epidemic anatomized|journal=Medical History|volume=41|issue=3|pages=362\u2013384|doi=10.1017/s0025727300062724|pmid=9327632}}\n* Flood, John L. \"Englischer Schwei\u00df und deutscher Flei\u00df. Ein Beitrag zur Buchhandelsgeschichte des 16. Jahrhunderts,\" in ''The German book in Wolfenb\u00fcttel and abroad. Studies presented to Ulrich Kopp in his retirement,'' ed. William A. Kelly & J\u00fcrgen Beyer [Studies in reading and book culture 1] (Tartu: University of Tartu Press, 2014), pp.&nbsp;119\u2013178. {{in lang|de}}\n*{{cite journal|doi=10.1056/NEJM199702203360812|pmid=9023099|title=The English Sweating Sickness, 1485 to 1551|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=336|issue=8|pages=580\u20132|year=1997|last1=Thwaites|first1=Guy|last2=Taviner|first2=Mark|last3=Gant|first3=Vanya}}\n*{{cite journal|pmid=7037928|year=1981|last1=Wylie|first1=J. A.|title=The English Sweating sickness (sudor Anglicus): A reappraisal|journal=Journal of the History of Medicine and Allied Sciences|volume=36|issue=4|pages=425\u201345|last2=Collier|first2=L. H.|doi=10.1093/jhmas/xxxvi.4.425}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB     =\n| ICD10          =\n| ICD9           = {{ICD9|078.2}}\n| ICDO           =\n| OMIM           =\n| MedlinePlus    =\n| eMedicineSubj  =\n| eMedicineTopic =\n| MeshID         = D018614\n}}\n* [http://www.abc.net.au/rn/ockhamsrazor/stories/2007/2039403.htm ''Sweating Fever''] Jim Leavesley commemorates the 500th anniversary of the first outbreak \u2013 transcript of talk on ''Ockham's Razor'' ABC [[Radio National]]\n*[http://www.csuchico.edu/geop/Flash%20Gallery/Pittman.swf The Curious Case of the English Sweating Sickness], contains a map of the disease dispersion created and mapped by Kirstyn Pittman from [[California State University, Chico]] (requires [[Adobe Flash]])\n*[http://discovermagazine.com/1997/jun/thesweatingsickn1161 \"The Sweating Sickness Returns\", ''Discover Magazine'', 1 June 1997]\n\n{{Viral diseases}}\n{{Epidemics}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sweating Sickness}}\n[[Category:1485 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:1551 disestablishments in England]]\n[[Category:15th-century epidemics]]\n[[Category:16th-century epidemics]]\n[[Category:1485 in Europe]]\n[[Category:1507 in Europe]]\n[[Category:1517 in Europe]]\n[[Category:1528 in Europe]]\n[[Category:1551 in Europe]]\n[[Category:1485 in England]]\n[[Category:1517 in England]]\n[[Category:1528 in England]]\n[[Category:1551 in England]]\n[[Category:Ailments of unknown cause]]\n[[Category:Retrospective diagnosis]]\n[[Category:History of medicine]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Mortee", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e15th century:correct plural of lord mayor ('lord' modifies 'mayor', not the other way around as in solicitors general)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweating_sickness"}
{"title_page": "Glycoazodyes", "text_new": "'''Glycoazodyes''' (or GADs) are a family of \"naturalised\" [[synthetic dye]]s, so called because they are the conjugation of common commercial [[azo dyes]] with a [[sugar]] through a \"linker\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Bartalucci|first=Giuditta|last2=Bianchini|first2=Roberto|last3=Catelani|first3=Giorgio|last4=D'Andrea|first4=Felicia|last5=Guazzelli|first5=Lorenzo|date=February 2007|title=Naturalised Dyes: A Simple Straightforward Synthetic Route to a New Class of Dyes \u2013 Glycoazodyes (GADs)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1002/ejoc.200600686|journal=European Journal of Organic Chemistry|volume=2007|issue=4|pages=588\u2013595|doi=10.1002/ejoc.200600686|issn=1434-193X}}</ref> This principle is summarised in the scheme below.\n\n[[Image:GAD diagram.gif|center]]\n\n== Generations, Structure, and Synthesis ==\n\n=== First-generation ===\nThe first-generation of Glycoazodyes was first reported in 2007. These Glycoazodyes use a [[Ester|diester]] linker, specifically a [[Succinic acid|succinyl]] bridge. An [[ester]] group bonds the sugar to an n-[[alkane]] spacer, and the spacer bonds to the dye through another [[ester]] group.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==== Synthesis ====\nFirst-generation Glycoazodyes are synthesized using [[glucose]], [[galactose]] or [[lactose]] as the sugar group. The point of [[Ester|esterification]] is controlled by selectively protecting and deprotecting alcohol groups on the sugar, or by choosing azo dyes with different alcohol group positions.\u00a0 Either the dye or the sugar group can be [[Succinylation|succinylated]] by reacting a free alcohol group with [[succinic anhydride]]. The resulting hemisuccinate then reacts with a free alcohol group on either the dye or the sugar. The condensation product is then deprotected.<ref name=\":0\" /> \u00a0 \u00a0\n\n=== Second-generation ===\nThe second-generation of Glycoazodyes was first reported in 2008. These Glycoazodyes use an etherel linker. An ether group bonds the sugar and the dye to an n-[[alkane]] spacer, and the spacer bonds to the dye through another ether group. Like first-generation Glycoazodyes, second-generation Glycoazodyes use glucose, galactose or lactose as the sugar group.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n=== Third-generation ===\nThe third-generation of Glycoazodyes was first reported in 2015. These Glycoazodyes use an amido-ester linker. An [[amide]] group bonds the sugar to an n-[[alkane]] spacer, and the spacer is bonded to the dye through an [[ester]] group.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Guazzelli|first=Lorenzo|last2=Catelani|first2=Giorgio|last3=D\u2019Andrea|first3=Felicia|date=2015|title=A New Generation of Glycoconjugated Azo Dyes Based on Aminosugars|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1155/2015/235763|journal=International Journal of Carbohydrate Chemistry|volume=2015|pages=1\u20137|doi=10.1155/2015/235763|issn=1687-9341}}</ref>\u00a0 \n\n== Properties ==\nA variety of fabrics such as [[wool]], [[silk]], [[nylon]], [[polyester]], [[Acrylic fiber|polyacrylic]], [[Cellulose acetate|polyacetate]], and [[polyurethane]] may be dyed with Glycoazodyes under moderate temperatures and pressures in aqueous solutions.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Bianchini|first=Roberto|last2=Catelani|first2=Giorgio|last3=Cecconi|first3=Riccardo|last4=D'Andrea|first4=Felicia|last5=Guazzelli|first5=Lorenzo|last6=Isaad|first6=Jalal|last7=Rolla|first7=Massimo|date=January 2008|title=Ethereal Glycoconjugated Azodyes (GADs): A New Group of Water-Soluble, Naturalised Dyes|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1002/ejoc.200700632|journal=European Journal of Organic Chemistry|volume=2008|issue=3|pages=444\u2013454|doi=10.1002/ejoc.200700632|issn=1434-193X}}</ref> First-generation Glycoazodyes dye [[cotton]] poorly.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, second-generation Glycoazodyes dye [[cotton]] effectively.<ref name=\":1\" /> \u00a0[[Wool]] dyed with Glycoazodyes shows good [[Lightfastness|fastness]] when exposed to\u00a0the [[International Organization for Standardization|ISO]] 105-C06 washing and [[International Organization for Standardization|ISO]] 105 X12 rubbing tests. <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Bianchini|first=Roberto|last2=Catelani|first2=Giorgio|last3=Cecconi|first3=Riccardo|last4=D\u2019Andrea|first4=Felicia|last5=Frino|first5=Elena|last6=Isaad|first6=Jalal|last7=Rolla|first7=Massimo|date=2008|title=\u2018Naturalization\u2019 of textile disperse dyes through glycoconjugation: the case of a bis(2-hydroxyethyl) group containing azo dye|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.carres.2008.02.009|journal=Carbohydrate Research|volume=343|issue=12|pages=2067\u20132074|doi=10.1016/j.carres.2008.02.009|issn=0008-6215|via=}}</ref>\n\nGlycoazodyes vary in their water solubility. They may be soluble in cold to warm water and may dissolve after stirring or upon addition.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nMinor variations in [[Absorption spectroscopy|absorption spectra]] occur when Glycoazodye solutions are prepared, using water, acetone, or methanol solvents.<ref name=\":0\" /> Converting a parent [[azo dye]] to a Glycoazodye also produces a small [[Hypsochromic shift|hypsochromic]] shift in the absorption spectra. \n\n== Environmental impact ==\nSeveral properties may make Glycoazodyes an environmentally friendly alternative to traditional [[synthetic dyes]]. The increased hydrophilicity of Glycoazodyes allows for the elimination of [[surfactant]]s, [[mordant]]s, and [[Salt (chemistry)|salts]], during the dyeing process and permits the aqueous dying of a variety of [[textile]]s at moderate temperatures and pressures. The unique structure may also allow for the treatment of textile effluent through biological means. ''[[Fusarium oxysporum]]'' efficiently decolourizes the first-generation Glycoazodye 4-{N,N-Bis[2-(D-galactopyranos-6-yloxy)ethyl]-amino}azobenzene. Various other [[Ascomycota]] fungi show a similar potential to decolourise Glycoazodyes, but to a lesser extent. Detoxification has been measured, using the ''[[Daphnia magna]]'' acute toxicity test, showing a 92% dye detoxification after 6 days. This detoxification method produces low concentrations of [[nitrobenzene]], [[aniline|aniline,]] and [[nitrosobenzene]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Porri|first=Aimone|last2=Baroncelli|first2=Riccardo|last3=Guglielminetti|first3=Lorenzo|last4=Sarrocco|first4=Sabrina|last5=Guazzelli|first5=Lorenzo|last6=Forti|first6=Maurizio|last7=Catelani|first7=Giorgio|last8=Valentini|first8=Giorgio|last9=Bazzichi|first9=Agostino|last10=Franceschi|first10=Massimiliano|last11=Vannacci|first11=Giovanni|date=January 2011|title=Fusarium oxysporum degradation and detoxification of a new textile-glycoconjugate azo dye (GAD)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.funbio.2010.10.001|journal=Fungal Biology|volume=115|issue=1|pages=30\u201337|doi=10.1016/j.funbio.2010.10.001|issn=1878-6146}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/ejoc.200600686/abstract\n\n== References ==\n{{Note|Bartalucci}}\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Dyes]]\n\n\n{{organic-chem-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Glycoazodyes''' (or GADs) are a family of \"naturalised\" [[synthetic dye]]s, so called because they are the conjugation of common commercial [[azo dyes]] with a [[sugar]] through a \"linker\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Bartalucci|first=Giuditta|last2=Bianchini|first2=Roberto|last3=Catelani|first3=Giorgio|last4=D'Andrea|first4=Felicia|last5=Guazzelli|first5=Lorenzo|date=February 2007|title=Naturalised Dyes: A Simple Straightforward Synthetic Route to a New Class of Dyes \u2013 Glycoazodyes (GADs)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1002/ejoc.200600686|journal=European Journal of Organic Chemistry|volume=2007|issue=4|pages=588\u2013595|doi=10.1002/ejoc.200600686|issn=1434-193X}}</ref> This principle is summarised in the scheme below.\n\n[[Image:GAD diagram.gif|center]]\n\n== Generations, Structure, and Synthesis ==\n\n=== First-generation ===\nThe first-generation of Glycoazodyes was first reported in 2007. These Glycoazodyes use a [[Ester|diester]] linker, specifically a [[Succinic acid|succinyl]] bridge. An [[ester]] group bonds the sugar to an n-[[alkane]] spacer, and the spacer bonds to the dye through another [[ester]] group.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==== Synthesis ====\nFirst-generation Glycoazodyes are synthesized using [[glucose]], [[galactose]] or [[lactose]] as the sugar group. The point of [[Ester|esterification]] is controlled by selectively protecting and deprotecting alcohol groups on the sugar, or by choosing azo dyes with different alcohol group positions.\u00a0 Either the dye or the sugar group can be [[Succinylation|succinylated]] by reacting a free alcohol group with [[succinic anhydride]]. The resulting hemisuccinate then reacts with a free alcohol group on either the dye or the sugar. The condensation product is then deprotected.<ref name=\":0\" /> \u00a0 \u00a0\n\n=== Second-generation ===\nThe second-generation of Glycoazodyes was first reported in 2008. These Glycoazodyes use an etherel linker. An ether group bonds the sugar and the dye to an n-[[alkane]] spacer, and the spacer bonds to the dye through another ether group. Like first-generation Glycoazodyes, second-generation Glycoazodyes use glucose, galactose or lactose as the sugar group.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n=== Third-generation ===\nThe third-generation of Glycoazodyes was first reported in 2015. These Glycoazodyes use an amido-ester linker. An [[amide]] group bonds the sugar to an n-[[alkane]] spacer, and the spacer is bonded to the dye through an [[ester]] group.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Guazzelli|first=Lorenzo|last2=Catelani|first2=Giorgio|last3=D\u2019Andrea|first3=Felicia|date=2015|title=A New Generation of Glycoconjugated Azo Dyes Based on Aminosugars|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1155/2015/235763|journal=International Journal of Carbohydrate Chemistry|volume=2015|pages=1\u20137|doi=10.1155/2015/235763|issn=1687-9341}}</ref>\u00a0 \n\n== Properties ==\nA variety of fabrics such as [[wool]], [[silk]], [[nylon]], [[polyester]], [[Acrylic fiber|polyacrylic]], [[Cellulose acetate|polyacetate]], and [[polyurethane]] may be dyed with Glycoazodyes under moderate temperatures and pressures in aqueous solutions.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Bianchini|first=Roberto|last2=Catelani|first2=Giorgio|last3=Cecconi|first3=Riccardo|last4=D'Andrea|first4=Felicia|last5=Guazzelli|first5=Lorenzo|last6=Isaad|first6=Jalal|last7=Rolla|first7=Massimo|date=January 2008|title=Ethereal Glycoconjugated Azodyes (GADs): A New Group of Water-Soluble, Naturalised Dyes|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1002/ejoc.200700632|journal=European Journal of Organic Chemistry|volume=2008|issue=3|pages=444\u2013454|doi=10.1002/ejoc.200700632|issn=1434-193X}}</ref> First-generation Glycoazodyes dye [[cotton]] poorly.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, second-generation Glycoazodyes dye [[cotton]] effectively.<ref name=\":1\" /> \u00a0[[Wool]] dyed with Glycoazodyes shows good [[Lightfastness|fastness]] when exposed to\u00a0the [[International Organization for Standardization|ISO]] 105-C06 washing and [[International Organization for Standardization|ISO]] 105 X12 rubbing tests. <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Bianchini|first=Roberto|last2=Catelani|first2=Giorgio|last3=Cecconi|first3=Riccardo|last4=D\u2019Andrea|first4=Felicia|last5=Frino|first5=Elena|last6=Isaad|first6=Jalal|last7=Rolla|first7=Massimo|date=2008|title=\u2018Naturalization\u2019 of textile disperse dyes through glycoconjugation: the case of a bis(2-hydroxyethyl) group containing azo dye|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.carres.2008.02.009|journal=Carbohydrate Research|volume=343|issue=12|pages=2067\u20132074|doi=10.1016/j.carres.2008.02.009|issn=0008-6215|via=}}</ref>\n\nGlycoazodyes vary in their water solubility. They may be soluble in cold to warm water and may dissolve after stirring or upon addition.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nMinor variations in [[Absorption spectroscopy|absorption spectra]] occur when Glycoazodye solutions are prepared, using water, acetone, or methanol solvents.<ref name=\":0\" /> Converting a parent [[azo dye]] to a Glycoazodye also produces a small [[Hypsochromic shift|hypsochromic]] shift in the absorption spectra. \n\n== Environmental impact ==\nSeveral properties may make Glycoazodyes an environmentally friendly alternative to traditional [[synthetic dyes]]. The increased hydrophilicity of Glycoazodyes allows for the elimination of [[surfactant]]s, [[mordant]]s, and [[Salt (chemistry)|salts]], during the dyeing process and permits the aqueous dying of a variety of [[textile]]s at moderate temperatures and pressures. The unique structure may also allow for the treatment of textile effluent through biological means. ''[[Fusarium oxysporum]]'' efficiently decolourizes the first-generation Glycoazodye 4-{N,N-Bis[2-(D-galactopyranos-6-yloxy)ethyl]-amino}azobenzene. Various other [[Ascomycota]] fungi show a similar potential to decolourises Glycoazodyes, but to a lesser extent. Detoxification has been measured, using the ''[[Daphnia magna]]'' acute toxicity test, showing a 92% dye detoxification after 6 days. This detoxification method produces low concentrations of [[nitrobenzene]], [[aniline|aniline,]] and [[nitrosobenzene]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Porri|first=Aimone|last2=Baroncelli|first2=Riccardo|last3=Guglielminetti|first3=Lorenzo|last4=Sarrocco|first4=Sabrina|last5=Guazzelli|first5=Lorenzo|last6=Forti|first6=Maurizio|last7=Catelani|first7=Giorgio|last8=Valentini|first8=Giorgio|last9=Bazzichi|first9=Agostino|last10=Franceschi|first10=Massimiliano|last11=Vannacci|first11=Giovanni|date=January 2011|title=Fusarium oxysporum degradation and detoxification of a new textile-glycoconjugate azo dye (GAD)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.funbio.2010.10.001|journal=Fungal Biology|volume=115|issue=1|pages=30\u201337|doi=10.1016/j.funbio.2010.10.001|issn=1878-6146}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/ejoc.200600686/abstract\n\n== References ==\n{{Note|Bartalucci}}\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Dyes]]\n\n\n{{organic-chem-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Oxleychristopher", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glycoazodyes"}
{"title_page": "West Side Line", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{stack|float=right|\n[[File:Empire_Connection_fr_61_St_jeh.jpg|thumb|300px|The West Side Line in Midtown Manhattan, seen in 2013. This section has been covered over since then.]]\n{{West Side Line}}\n}}\nThe '''West Side Line''', also called the '''West Side Freight Line''', is a [[railroad]] line on the west side of the [[New York City]] borough of [[Manhattan]]. North of [[Penn Station (New York)|Penn Station]], from  [[34th Street (Manhattan)|34th Street]], the line is used by [[Amtrak]] passenger service heading north via [[Albany, New York|Albany]] to [[Toronto]]; [[Montreal]]; [[Niagara Falls, New York|Niagara Falls]] and [[Buffalo, New York]]; [[Rutland (city), Vermont|Rutland, Vermont]]; and [[Chicago]]. South of Penn Station, a {{convert|1.45|mi|km|adj=on}} elevated section of the line abandoned since 1980 has been transformed into an elevated park called the [[High Line]]. The south section of the park from [[Gansevoort Street]] to 20th Street opened in 2009 and the second section up to 30th Street opened in 2011, while the final section to 34th Street opened in 2014.\n\n==Hudson River Railroad==\n[[File:New York City Railroads ca 1900.png|thumb|left|New York City Railroads {{circa|1900}}]]\n[[File:(King1893NYC) pg820 NEW-YORK CENTRAL & HUDSON-RIVER FREIGHT DEPOT ON HUDSON STREET.jpg|thumb|left|Hudson River R.R. St. John's Depot {{circa|1890}}]]\n\nThe West Side Line was built by the [[Hudson River Railroad]], which completed the {{convert|40|mi|spell=in}} to [[Peekskill, New York|Peekskill]] on September 29, 1849, opened to [[Poughkeepsie (city), New York|Poughkeepsie]] by the end of that year, and extended to [[Albany, New York|Albany]] in 1851. The city terminus was at the junction of [[Chambers Street (Manhattan)|Chambers]] and [[Hudson Street (Manhattan)|Hudson Streets]]; the track was laid along Hudson, [[Canal Street (Manhattan)|Canal]], and West Streets, to [[Tenth Avenue (Manhattan)|Tenth Avenue]], which it followed to the upper city station at [[34th Street (Manhattan)|34th Street]]. Over this part of the right-of-way, the rails were laid at grade along the streets, and since by the corporation regulations locomotives were not allowed, the cars were drawn by a [[dummy engine]], which, according to an 1851 description, consumed its own smoke. While passing through the city the train of cars was preceded by a man on horseback known as a \"West Side cowboy\" or \"Tenth Avenue cowboy\" who gave notice of its approach by blowing a horn.<ref>{{cite book |title=Hudson River and the Hudson River Rail-Road |url=http://www.catskillarchive.com/rrextra/abnyh.Html |accessdate=September 18, 2015 |year=1851 |publisher=Bradbury & Guild |location=Boston |page=12}}</ref><ref>[http://blog.thehighline.org/2008/03/12/photo-of-the-week-west-side-cowboy-twofer/ Highline Photo of the Week] West Side Cowboy</ref>\n\nAt 34th Street the right-of-way curved into [[11th Avenue (Manhattan)|Eleventh Avenue]], the dummy engine was detached, and the regular locomotive took the train. As far as [[60th Street (Manhattan)|60th Street]], the track was at street level. The first cut was at Fort Washington Point. The railroad crossed [[Spuyten Duyvil Creek]] on a drawbridge; a fatal wreck occurred there January 13, 1882 when the Atlantic Express, stopped on the line, was rear-ended by a local train, telescoping the last two palace cars, where the stoves and lamps were upset and ignited the woodwork and upholstery.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fatal Disaster on the Hudson River Railroad |url=http://www.catskillarchive.com/rrextra/wksdfl.Html |newspaper=[[Frank Leslie's Weekly]] |date=January 21, 1882 |accessdate=April 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 1867 the [[New York Central Railroad]] and Hudson River Railroad were united by [[Cornelius Vanderbilt]], being merged in 1869 to form the [[New York Central and Hudson River Railroad]]. The railroad acquired the former Episcopal church's [[St. John's Park]] property and built a large freight depot at Beach and Varick streets which opened in 1868. The tracks south to Chambers Street were then removed.<ref>Joint Report of the New York, New Jersey Port and Harbor development Commission, 1917</ref> In 1871, the [[Spuyten Duyvil and Port Morris Railroad]] ([[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]]) opened, and most passenger trains were rerouted into the new [[Grand Central Depot]] via that line along the northeast bank of the [[Harlem River]] and the [[New York and Harlem Railroad]] ([[Harlem Line]]), also part of the New York Central system. The old line south of [[Spuyten Duyvil, Bronx|Spuyten Duyvil]] remained for freight to the docks along Manhattan's west side and minimal passenger service to the [[West Side station]] on [[Chambers Street (Manhattan)|Chambers Street]] (used until 1916).\n\n== Grade separation ==\n[[File:Rail entry W82 St snowy jeh.JPG|thumb|left|View from under Henry Hudson Parkway toward maintenance gate to tracks]]\nAs the city grew, congestion worsened on the west side. Eventually plans were drawn up for a grade-separated line. The [[West Side Elevated Highway]] was built with the line's grade separation in the 1930s. Work on the highway&nbsp;\u2013 named for Manhattan Borough President [[Julius Miller]], who championed it&nbsp;\u2013 began in 1925, and the first section was dedicated June 28, 1934. This included a new elevated eight-track freight terminal at [[St. John's Park]], located several blocks north of the old one, with a south edge at [[Spring Street (Manhattan)|Spring Street]]. North of there, an elevated structure (the present-day [[High Line]]) carried two tracks north on the west side of [[Washington Street (Manhattan)|Washington Street]], curving onto the east side of [[Tenth Avenue (Manhattan)|Tenth Avenue]] at [[14th Street (Manhattan)|14th Street]], then crossing Tenth Avenue at [[17th Street (Manhattan)|17th Street]] and heading north along its west side. Just south of the [[West Side Yard|Pennsylvania Station rail yard at 31st\u201333rd Streets]], the line turned west on the north side of [[30th Street (Manhattan)|30th Street]], then north just east of the [[West Side Highway]]. The northernmost bridge crossed [[34th Street (Manhattan)|34th Street]], and a ramp took it back to [[Eleventh Avenue (Manhattan)|Eleventh Avenue]] south of [[35th Street (Manhattan)|35th Street]]. The elevated line was built through the second or third floors of several buildings along the route; others were served directly by elevated sidings.<ref name=\"nyt19340603\">L.H. Robbins, [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1934/06/03/95046347.pdf \"Transforming the West Side: A Huge Project Marches On],\" New York Times, June 3, 1934</ref><ref name=\"railroad.net improvement\">{{cite web | title=NYC West Side Improvement | url=http://www.railroad.net/nyc/westside.html | website=railroad.net | archivedate=March 1, 2000 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000301162857/http://www.railroad.net/nyc/westside.html | accessdate=May 17, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1937 the tracks along Eleventh Avenue were bypassed by a below-grade line, passing under the 35th Street intersection and running north just west of Tenth Avenue before slowly curving northwest, passing under Eleventh Avenue at [[59th Street (Manhattan)|59th Street]] and rejoining the original alignment.<ref name=nyt19340603/><ref name=\"railroad.net improvement\"/>\n\n[[File:Spuyten Duyvil Bridge north fixed span from gap jeh.jpg|thumb|Spuyten Duyvil Bridge, Bronx end, when the swing is open]]\nAround the same time, New York City parks commissioner [[Robert Moses]] covered the line from 72nd Street north to 120th Street with an expansion of [[Riverside Park (Manhattan)|Riverside Park]]. His project, called the ''West Side Improvement'', was twice as expensive as the [[Hoover Dam]] and created the [[Henry Hudson Parkway]], as well as a [[Freedom Tunnel|railroad tunnel]] through the park. The large [[Riverside South, Manhattan#60th Street Rail Yard|60th Street Yard]] served as the dividing point between the two-track realignment and a wider four-track line to the north. North of 123rd Street, the line became elevated between the Henry Hudson Parkway and [[Riverside Drive (Manhattan)|Riverside Drive]] before returning to the surface and crossing under the Parkway to its west side near [[159th Street (Manhattan)|159th Street]]. It continues along the shore of the [[Hudson River]] to the [[Spuyten Duyvil Bridge]], a [[swing bridge]] across the [[Harlem Ship Canal]] ([[Spuyten Duyvil Creek]]), before merging with the [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]] just north of the bridge.<ref name=\"railroad.net improvement\"/>\n\nIn addition to serving the industrial and dock areas of the [[Lower West Side, Manhattan|Lower West Side]], the line was the primary route for produce and meat into New York, serving warehouses in the [[West Village]], [[Chelsea, Manhattan|Chelsea]], and the [[Meatpacking District, Manhattan|Meatpacking District]], as well as serving the [[James Farley Post Office]] and private freight services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://railroad.net/articles/railfanning/westside/index.php|title=RAILROAD.NET - New York Central's 1934 West Side Improvement|work=railroad.net}}</ref>\n\n==Donald Trump and Riverside South==\n[[File:Riverside-south-overview.jpg|thumb|left|Looking north in Riverside Park South.  Trump Place and West Side Highway are on the right and [[New York Central Railroad 69th Street Transfer Bridge|69th Street float transfer bridge]] on the left.]]\nThe [[New York Central Railroad]] was merged into [[Penn Central]] in 1968 and [[Conrail]] in 1976. Conrail continued to operate freight along the West Side Line until the 1980s.\n\n[[Donald Trump]] optioned the 60th Street Yard in 1974.<ref name=\"nyt20050601\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/01/nyregion/trump-group-selling-west-side-parcel-for-18-billion.html|title=Trump Group Selling West Side Parcel for $1.8 Billion|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|date=June 1, 2005|website=The New York Times|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> [[Riverside South, Manhattan|Riverside South]], the development project he ultimately began there, was then the city's biggest private residential development; it faced opposition from many people living on the [[Upper West Side]].<ref>Bruce Weber, [https://www.nytimes.com/1992/07/22/nyregion/debate-on-trump-s-west-side-proposal.html \"Debate on Trump's West Side Proposal],\" New York Times, July 22, 1992</ref> To obtain approval of his project, Trump agreed to substantially reduce the size of his ambitions,<ref>Todd S. Purdum, [https://www.nytimes.com/1991/03/06/nyregion/trump-revises-project-plan-for-west-side.html \"Trump Revises Project Plan for West Side\"], New York Times, March 6, 1991.</ref> build Riverside Park South on {{convert|23|acre|ha}} of the yard,<ref name=\"home.jps.net 20042\">{{cite web|url=http://home.jps.net/~riversidesouth/crd_newsletter01-04.html|title=The West Side Rethinks Donald Trump's Riverside South|last=Vitullo-Martin|first=Julia|date=January 19, 2004|website=home.jps.net|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> and donate the park and the right-of-way for a relocated highway to the city.<ref>Alan Finder, [https://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/22/nyregion/trump-yields-to-demand-on-housing.html \"Trump Yields to Demands on Housing,\"] New York Times, October 22, 1992.</ref>\n\nThe line north of 31st Street was acquired by Amtrak. The southernmost part of the [[High Line]] (south of [[Bank Street (Manhattan)|Bank Street]]) had been removed in the 1960s;<ref name=\"nycarch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc-architecture.com/CHE/CHE029-TheHighLine.htm|title=The High Line|work=NYC Architecture}}</ref> the structure from Bank to Gansevoort Streets was removed some 20 years later.<ref name=\"villager261\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thevillager.com/villager_261/newspaperwasthere.html|title=Newspaper was there at High Line's birth and now its rebirth|last=Amateau|first=Albert|date=April 30 \u2013 May 6, 2008|work=[[The Villager (Manhattan)|The Villager]]|issue=48|volume=77|accessdate=August 12, 2011}}</ref> The northernmost block of the High Line viaduct, between 34th and 35th Streets, was rerouted to the south of 34th Street in the 1980s because the ramp to 35th Street was demolished as part of the [[Javits Center]]'s construction. However, the realigned ramp was never used.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Greenstein | first=J | title=WEST SIDE STORY : THE RISE AND FALL OF MANHATTAN'S HIGH LINE | journal=Trains | volume=62 | issue=3 | date=2002-04-01 | issn=0041-0934 | url=https://trid.trb.org/view/709658 | access-date=2018-07-10 | page=}}</ref> By mid-2005, the rest of the High Line was owned by [[CSX]], which acquired it after the 1999 breakup of Conrail.<ref name=\"greatmus\">{{cite episode|title=Elevated Thinking: The High Line in New York City|series=Great Museums|first1=Chesney|last1=Doyle|first2=Susan|last2=Spann|year=2014}}</ref>\n\n==Empire Connection==\nThe '''Empire Connection''' allows [[Amtrak]]'s passenger trains traveling on the [[Empire Corridor]] from [[Albany, New York|Albany]] in [[upstate New York]], and beyond, to enter [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]]. Before its construction, Empire Service trains came into [[Grand Central Terminal]], requiring passengers bound for [[Northeast Corridor]] trains to transfer to Penn Station via [[Shuttle bus#Types of service|shuttle bus]], [[taxicab]], [[New York City Subway|subway]] or on foot.<ref>Penn Station could be reached from the Empire Corridor, but only via an impractical route from [[the Bronx]], via the [[New Haven Line]], that then backtracked several miles to the north, to [[Pelham Manor, New York|Pelham Manor]], to the Northeast Corridor line.</ref> This was a legacy of the fact that the Empire Service lines had previously been part of the [[New York Central Railroad]], who built and owner Grand Central, while Penn Station was owned by the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]]. The two stations have never been connected, even after the PRR and New York Central merged as [[Penn Central Transportation Company|Penn Central]] in 1968 and after Amtrak took over intercity rail service in 1971.\n\n[[File:Spuyten Duyvil joint.jpg|thumb|North end of the Empire Connection, joining Metro-North's [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]]]]\n\nWhen the [[West Side Yard]] for the [[Long Island Rail Road]] was built on the west side of Manhattan in 1986, a tunnel was built under it connecting Penn Station to the West Side Line just west of [[Eleventh Avenue (Manhattan)|Eleventh Avenue]], near the [[Javits Center]]. The project severed the southernmost part of the West Side Line, the High Line viaduct, from the rest of the West Side Line.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Air Above Rail Yards Still Free |first=Mary |last=Voboril |newspaper=[[Newsday]] |location=New York |date=March 26, 2005}}</ref> When additional funding later became available, one track along the northern part of the West Side Line was rebuilt for passenger service and named the Empire Connection. A short section of single track into Penn Station was [[railway electrification|electrified]] using [[third rail]] and [[overhead line|overhead catenary]], since [[diesel locomotive|diesel locomotives]] are not allowed in Penn Station's tunnels. North of 41st Street, the single track expands into two tracks and electrification on the line ends. A [[wye (railroad)|wye]] was constructed next to Track 2 (the westernmost track) to allow diesels to turn around. South of 49th Street, there is a crossover from Track 1 (the easternmost track) to Track 2, and another siding splits off Track 2 at 49th Street.  The Empire Connection was double-tracked north of 39th Street to south of the [[Spuyten Duyvil Bridge]] in the mid-1990s.\n\nOn April 7, 1991, all of Amtrak's trains departing for or arriving from Albany and points north began using the Empire Connection into Penn Station, ending service to Grand Central.<ref>{{cite news |title=Travel Advisory; Grand Central Trains Rerouted To Penn Station |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/04/07/travel/travel-advisory-grand-central-trains-rerouted-to-penn-station.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 7, 1991 |accessdate=February 7, 2010}}</ref> Transportation planners had long envisioned consolidating all intercity service to New York at Penn Station, but those efforts never got beyond the planning stages until the 1980s. Besides being more convenient for passengers, many of whom had balked at taking the train to New York City due to the difficulty of transferring between stations, this saved Amtrak the expense of operating two stations in New York City. Additionally, Amtrak had to pay $600,000 per year to the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]], operator of Grand Central, to use that station's tracks.<ref name=\"AutoVN-77\">{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=Kirk|title=Amtrak Trains To Stop Using Grand Central|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 7, 1988|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/07/07/nyregion/amtrak-trains-to-stop-using-grand-central.html|accessdate=November 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"AutoDR-83\">{{cite news|last=Barron|first=James|title=Riding the Past From Grand Central|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 8, 1991|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/04/08/nyregion/riding-the-past-from-grand-central.html|accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nUnder the [[Penn Station Access]] project, [[Metro-North Railroad]] is studying ways it could also serve Penn Station. One alternative being studied would run some [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]] commuter trains into Penn Station via the Empire Connection, possibly with new station stops at West 125th and West 62nd Streets.\n\n== High Line park ==\n[[File:Highline NYC 3705376658 529a375621.jpg|thumb|A section of the High Line at Tenth Avenue and 17th Street]]\n{{Main|High Line}}\nIn the early 1980s, as the connections to Penn Station were created, the line south of 34th Street was disconnected from the rest of the [[National rail network|U.S. railway system]]. This portion of the line, entirely on an elevated viaduct, stood dormant for over thirty years. This viaduct, now called the High Line, has been turned into an elevated park which opened in phases from June 2009 to fall 2014.<ref name=\"marritz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wnyc.org/articles/wnyc-news/2011/jun/07/high-line/|last=Marritz|first=Ilya|title=As the High Line Grows, Business Falls in Love with a Public Park|publisher=[[WNYC]]|date=June 7, 2011|accessdate=June 8, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"browne\">{{Cite news\n|url=http://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/06/07/high-notes-new-art-on-the-high-line/|title=High Notes - New Art on the High Line|last=Browne|first=Alex|date=June 7, 2011|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"pesce\">{{Cite news\n|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/ny_local/2011/06/07/2011-06-07_hotly_anticipated_second_section_of_the_high_line_opens_adding_10_blocks_of_elev.html|title=Hotly anticipated second section of the High Line opens, adding 10 blocks of elevated park space|last=Pesce|first=Nicole Lyn|date=June 7, 2011|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303701304579550201916425732 | title=Artist's 'Ruins' Rise on the High Line - WSJ.com | work=[[Wall Street Journal]] | date=May 11, 2014 | accessdate=May 12, 2014 | last=Battaglia | first=Andy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehighline.org/about/high-line-at-the-rail-yards | title=High Line at the Rail Yards | work=Friends of the High Line | accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[East Side Access]], companion project to Penn Station Access\n* [[Freedom Tunnel]]\n\n==References==\n\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n*{{Cite journal|first=Theodore W.|last=Scull|title=Change at Penn Station: an opportunity|work=[[Trains (magazine)|Trains]]|date= August 1991}}\n*{{Cite journal|first=Bob|last=Johnston|title=New Amtrak cuts signal a long siege|work=[[Trains (magazine)|Trains]]|date=June 1995}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title|from=West Side Line (NYCRR)}}\n*[http://www.railroad.net/articles/railfanning/westside/ New York Central's 1934 West Side Improvement] (1934 pamphlet)\n*[http://www.columbia.edu/~brennan/abandoned/bronx.html Abandoned Stations - Bronx Railroad Stations] (includes the West Side Line in Manhattan)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:West Side Line (Nycrr)}}\n[[Category:New York Central Railroad lines]]\n[[Category:Rail infrastructure in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:West Side Line| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{stack|float=right|\n[[File:Empire_Connection_fr_61_St_jeh.jpg|thumb|300px|The West Side Line in Midtown Manhattan, seen in 2013. This section has been covered over since then.]]\n{{West Side Line}}\n}}\nThe '''West Side Line''', also called the '''West Side Freight Line''', is a [[railroad]] line on the west side of the [[New York City]] borough of [[Manhattan]]. North of [[Penn Station (New York)|Penn Station]], from  [[34th Street (Manhattan)|34th Street]], the line is used by [[Amtrak]] passenger service heading north via [[Albany, New York|Albany]] to [[Toronto]]; [[Montreal]]; [[Niagara Falls, New York|Niagara Falls]] and [[Buffalo, New York]]; [[Rutland (city), Vermont|Rutland, Vermont]]; and [[Chicago]]. South of Penn Station, a {{convert|1.45|mi|km|adj=on}} elevated section of the line abandoned since 1980 has been transformed into an elevated park called the [[High Line]]. The south section of the park from [[Gansevoort Street]] to 20th Street opened in 2009 and the second section up to 30th Street opened in 2011, while the final section to 34th Street opened in 2014.\n\n==Hudson River Railroad==\n[[File:New York City Railroads ca 1900.png|thumb|left|New York City Railroads {{circa|1900}}]]\n[[File:(King1893NYC) pg820 NEW-YORK CENTRAL & HUDSON-RIVER FREIGHT DEPOT ON HUDSON STREET.jpg|thumb|left|Hudson River R.R. St. John's Depot {{circa|1890}}]]\n\nThe West Side Line was built by the [[Hudson River Railroad]], which completed the {{convert|40|mi|spell=in}} to [[Peekskill, New York|Peekskill]] on September 29, 1849, opened to [[Poughkeepsie (city), New York|Poughkeepsie]] by the end of that year, and extended to [[Albany, New York|Albany]] in 1851. The city terminus was at the junction of [[Chambers Street (Manhattan)|Chambers]] and [[Hudson Street (Manhattan)|Hudson Streets]]; the track was laid along Hudson, [[Canal Street (Manhattan)|Canal]], and West Streets, to [[Tenth Avenue (Manhattan)|Tenth Avenue]], which it followed to the upper city station at [[34th Street (Manhattan)|34th Street]]. Over this part of the right-of-way, the rails were laid at grade along the streets, and since by the corporation regulations locomotives were not allowed, the cars were drawn by a [[dummy engine]], which, according to an 1851 description, consumed its own smoke. While passing through the city the train of cars was preceded by a man on horseback known as a \"West Side cowboy\" or \"Tenth Avenue cowboy\" who gave notice of its approach by blowing a horn.<ref>{{cite book |title=Hudson River and the Hudson River Rail-Road |url=http://www.catskillarchive.com/rrextra/abnyh.Html |accessdate=September 18, 2015 |year=1851 |publisher=Bradbury & Guild |location=Boston |page=12}}</ref><ref>[http://blog.thehighline.org/2008/03/12/photo-of-the-week-west-side-cowboy-twofer/ Highline Photo of the Week] West Side Cowboy</ref>\n\nAt 34th Street the right-of-way curved into [[11th Avenue (Manhattan)|Eleventh Avenue]], the dummy engine was detached, and the regular locomotive took the train. As far as [[60th Street (Manhattan)|60th Street]], the track was at street level. The first cut was at Fort Washington Point. The railroad crossed [[Spuyten Duyvil Creek]] on a drawbridge; a fatal wreck occurred there January 13, 1882 when the Atlantic Express, stopped on the line, was rear-ended by a local train, telescoping the last two palace cars, where the stoves and lamps were upset and ignited the woodwork and upholstery.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fatal Disaster on the Hudson River Railroad |url=http://www.catskillarchive.com/rrextra/wksdfl.Html |newspaper=[[Frank Leslie's Weekly]] |date=January 21, 1882 |accessdate=April 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 1867 the [[New York Central Railroad]] and Hudson River Railroad were united by [[Cornelius Vanderbilt]], being merged in 1869 to form the [[New York Central and Hudson River Railroad]]. The railroad acquired the former Episcopal church's [[St. John's Park]] property and built a large freight depot at Beach and Varick streets which opened in 1868. The tracks south to Chambers Street were then removed.<ref>Joint Report of the New York, New Jersey Port and Harbor development Commission, 1917</ref> In 1871, the [[Spuyten Duyvil and Port Morris Railroad]] ([[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]]) opened, and most passenger trains were rerouted into the new [[Grand Central Depot]] via that line along the northeast bank of the [[Harlem River]] and the [[New York and Harlem Railroad]] ([[Harlem Line]]), also part of the New York Central system. The old line south of [[Spuyten Duyvil, Bronx|Spuyten Duyvil]] remained for freight to the docks along Manhattan's west side and minimal passenger service to the [[West Side station]] on [[Chambers Street (Manhattan)|Chambers Street]] (used until 1916).\n\n== Grade separation ==\n[[File:Rail entry W82 St snowy jeh.JPG|thumb|left|View from under Henry Hudson Parkway toward maintenance gate to tracks]]\nAs the city grew, congestion worsened on the west side. Eventually plans were drawn up for a grade-separated line. The [[West Side Elevated Highway]] was built with the line's grade separation in the 1930s. Work on the highway&nbsp;\u2013 named for Manhattan Borough President [[Julius Miller]], who championed it&nbsp;\u2013 began in 1925, and the first section was dedicated June 28, 1934. This included a new elevated eight-track freight terminal at [[St. John's Park]], located several blocks north of the old one, with a south edge at [[Spring Street (Manhattan)|Spring Street]]. North of there, an elevated structure (the present-day [[High Line]]) carried two tracks north on the west side of [[Washington Street (Manhattan)|Washington Street]], curving onto the east side of [[Tenth Avenue (Manhattan)|Tenth Avenue]] at [[14th Street (Manhattan)|14th Street]], then crossing Tenth Avenue at [[17th Street (Manhattan)|17th Street]] and heading north along its west side. Just south of the [[West Side Yard|Pennsylvania Station rail yard at 31st\u201333rd Streets]], the line turned west on the north side of [[30th Street (Manhattan)|30th Street]], then north just east of the [[West Side Highway]]. The northernmost bridge crossed [[34th Street (Manhattan)|34th Street]], and a ramp took it back to [[Eleventh Avenue (Manhattan)|Eleventh Avenue]] south of [[35th Street (Manhattan)|35th Street]]. The elevated line was built through the second or third floors of several buildings along the route; others were served directly by elevated sidings.<ref name=\"nyt19340603\">L.H. Robbins, [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1934/06/03/95046347.pdf \"Transforming the West Side: A Huge Project Marches On],\" New York Times, June 3, 1934</ref><ref name=\"railroad.net improvement\">{{cite web | title=NYC West Side Improvement | url=http://www.railroad.net/nyc/westside.html | website=railroad.net | archivedate=March 1, 2000 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000301162857/http://www.railroad.net/nyc/westside.html | accessdate=May 17, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1937 the tracks along Eleventh Avenue were bypassed by a below-grade line, passing under the 35th Street intersection and running north just west of Tenth Avenue before slowly curving northwest, passing under Eleventh Avenue at [[59th Street (Manhattan)|59th Street]] and rejoining the original alignment.<ref name=nyt19340603/><ref name=\"railroad.net improvement\"/>\n\n[[File:Spuyten Duyvil Bridge north fixed span from gap jeh.jpg|thumb|Spuyten Duyvil Bridge, Bronx end, when the swing is open]]\nAround the same time, New York City parks commissioner [[Robert Moses]] covered the line from 72nd Street north to 120th Street with an expansion of [[Riverside Park (Manhattan)|Riverside Park]]. His project, called the ''West Side Improvement'', was twice as expensive as the [[Hoover Dam]] and created the [[Henry Hudson Parkway]], as well as a [[Freedom Tunnel|railroad tunnel]] through the park. The large [[Riverside South, Manhattan#60th Street Rail Yard|60th Street Yard]] served as the dividing point between the two-track realignment and a wider four-track line to the north. North of 123rd Street, the line became elevated between the Henry Hudson Parkway and [[Riverside Drive (Manhattan)|Riverside Drive]] before returning to the surface and crossing under the Parkway to its west side near [[159th Street (Manhattan)|159th Street]]. It continues along the shore of the [[Hudson River]] to the [[Spuyten Duyvil Bridge]], a [[swing bridge]] across the [[Harlem Ship Canal]] ([[Spuyten Duyvil Creek]]), before merging with the [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]] just north of the bridge.<ref name=\"railroad.net improvement\"/>\n\nIn addition to serving the industrial and dock areas of the [[Lower West Side, Manhattan|Lower West Side]], the line was the primary route for produce and meat into New York, serving warehouses in the [[West Village]], [[Chelsea, Manhattan|Chelsea]], and the [[Meatpacking District, Manhattan|Meatpacking District]], as well as serving the [[James Farley Post Office]] and private freight services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://railroad.net/articles/railfanning/westside/index.php|title=RAILROAD.NET - New York Central's 1934 West Side Improvement|work=railroad.net}}</ref>\n\n==Donald Trump and Riverside South==\n[[File:Riverside-south-overview.jpg|thumb|left|Looking north in Riverside Park South.  Trump Place and West Side Highway are on the right and [[New York Central Railroad 69th Street Transfer Bridge|69th Street float transfer bridge]] on the left.]]\nThe [[New York Central Railroad]] was merged into [[Penn Central]] in 1968 and [[Conrail]] in 1976. Conrail continued to operate freight along the West Side Line until the 1980s.\n\n[[Donald Trump]] optioned the 60th Street Yard in 1974.<ref name=\"nyt20050601\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/01/nyregion/trump-group-selling-west-side-parcel-for-18-billion.html|title=Trump Group Selling West Side Parcel for $1.8 Billion|last=Bagli|first=Charles V.|date=June 1, 2005|website=The New York Times|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> [[Riverside South, Manhattan|Riverside South]], the development project he ultimately began there, was then the city's biggest private residential development; it faced opposition from many people living on the [[Upper West Side]].<ref>Bruce Weber, [https://www.nytimes.com/1992/07/22/nyregion/debate-on-trump-s-west-side-proposal.html \"Debate on Trump's West Side Proposal],\" New York Times, July 22, 1992</ref> To obtain approval of his project, Trump agreed to substantially reduce the size of his ambitions,<ref>Todd S. Purdum, [https://www.nytimes.com/1991/03/06/nyregion/trump-revises-project-plan-for-west-side.html \"Trump Revises Project Plan for West Side\"], New York Times, March 6, 1991.</ref> build Riverside Park South on {{convert|23|acre|ha}} of the yard,<ref name=\"home.jps.net 20042\">{{cite web|url=http://home.jps.net/~riversidesouth/crd_newsletter01-04.html|title=The West Side Rethinks Donald Trump's Riverside South|last=Vitullo-Martin|first=Julia|date=January 19, 2004|website=home.jps.net|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> and donate the park and the right-of-way for a relocated highway to the city.<ref>Alan Finder, [https://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/22/nyregion/trump-yields-to-demand-on-housing.html \"Trump Yields to Demands on Housing,\"] New York Times, October 22, 1992.</ref>\n\nThe line north of 31st Street was acquired by Amtrak. The southernmost part of the [[High Line]] (south of [[Bank Street (Manhattan)|Bank Street]]) had been removed in the 1960s;<ref name=\"nycarch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc-architecture.com/CHE/CHE029-TheHighLine.htm|title=The High Line|work=NYC Architecture}}</ref> the structure from Bank to Gansevoort Streets was removed some 20 years later.<ref name=\"villager261\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thevillager.com/villager_261/newspaperwasthere.html|title=Newspaper was there at High Line's birth and now its rebirth|last=Amateau|first=Albert|date=April 30 \u2013 May 6, 2008|work=[[The Villager (Manhattan)|The Villager]]|issue=48|volume=77|accessdate=August 12, 2011}}</ref> The northernmost block of the High Line viaduct, between 34th and 35th Streets, was rerouted to the south of 34th Street in the 1980s because the ramp to 35th Street was demolished as part of the [[Javits Center]]'s construction. However, the realigned ramp was never used.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Greenstein | first=J | title=WEST SIDE STORY : THE RISE AND FALL OF MANHATTAN'S HIGH LINE | journal=Trains | volume=62 | issue=3 | date=2002-04-01 | issn=0041-0934 | url=https://trid.trb.org/view/709658 | access-date=2018-07-10 | page=}}</ref> By mid-2005, the rest of the High Line was owned by [[CSX]], which acquired it after the 1999 breakup of Conrail.<ref name=\"greatmus\">{{cite episode|title=Elevated Thinking: The High Line in New York City|series=Great Museums|first1=Chesney|last1=Doyle|first2=Susan|last2=Spann|year=2014}}</ref>\n\n==Empire Connection==\nThe '''Empire Connection''' allows [[Amtrak]]'s passenger trains traveling on the [[Empire Corridor]] from [[Albany, New York|Albany]] in [[upstate New York]], and beyond, to enter [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]]. Before its construction, Empire Corridor trains came into [[Grand Central Terminal]], requiring passengers bound for [[Northeast Corridor]] trains to transfer to Penn Station via [[Shuttle bus#Types of service|shuttle bus]], [[taxicab]], [[New York City Subway|subway]] or on foot.<ref>Penn Station could be reached from the Empire Corridor, but only via an impractical route from [[the Bronx]], via the [[New Haven Line]], that then backtracked several miles to the north, to [[Pelham Manor, New York|Pelham Manor]], to the Northeast Corridor line.</ref> This was a legacy of the fact that the Empire Corridor lines had previously been part of the [[New York Central Railroad]], longtime owner of Grand Central, while Penn Station was owned by the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]]. The two stations have never been connected, even after the PRR and New York Central merged as [[Penn Central Transportation Company|Penn Central]] in 1968 and after Amtrak took over intercity rail service in 1971.\n\n[[File:Spuyten Duyvil joint.jpg|thumb|North end of the Empire Connection, joining Metro-North's [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]]]]\n\nWhen the [[West Side Yard]] for the [[Long Island Rail Road]] was built on the west side of Manhattan in 1986, a tunnel was built under it connecting Penn Station to the West Side Line just west of [[Eleventh Avenue (Manhattan)|Eleventh Avenue]], near the [[Javits Center]]. The project severed the southernmost part of the West Side Line, the High Line viaduct, from the rest of the West Side Line.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Air Above Rail Yards Still Free |first=Mary |last=Voboril |newspaper=[[Newsday]] |location=New York |date=March 26, 2005}}</ref> When additional funding later became available, one track along the northern part of the West Side Line was rebuilt for passenger service and named the Empire Connection. A short section of single track into Penn Station was [[railway electrification|electrified]] using [[third rail]] and [[overhead line|overhead catenary]], since [[diesel locomotive|diesel locomotives]] are not allowed in Penn Station's tunnels. North of 41st Street, the single track expands into two tracks and electrification on the line ends. A [[wye (railroad)|wye]] was constructed next to Track 2 (the westernmost track) to allow diesels to turn around. South of 49th Street, there is a crossover from Track 1 (the easternmost track) to Track 2, and another siding splits off Track 2 at 49th Street.  The Empire Connection was double-tracked north of 39th Street to south of the [[Spuyten Duyvil Bridge]] in the mid-1990s.\n\nOn April 7, 1991, all of Amtrak's trains departing for or arriving from Albany and points north began using the Empire Connection into Penn Station, ending service to Grand Central.<ref>{{cite news |title=Travel Advisory; Grand Central Trains Rerouted To Penn Station |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/04/07/travel/travel-advisory-grand-central-trains-rerouted-to-penn-station.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 7, 1991 |accessdate=February 7, 2010}}</ref> Transportation planners had long envisioned consolidating all intercity service to New York at Penn Station, but those efforts never got beyond the planning stages until the 1980s. Besides being more convenient for passengers, many of whom had balked at taking the train to New York City due to the difficulty of transferring between stations, this saved Amtrak the expense of operating two stations in New York City. Additionally, Amtrak had to pay $600,000 per year to the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]], operator of Grand Central, to use that station's tracks.<ref name=\"AutoVN-77\">{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=Kirk|title=Amtrak Trains To Stop Using Grand Central|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 7, 1988|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/07/07/nyregion/amtrak-trains-to-stop-using-grand-central.html|accessdate=November 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"AutoDR-83\">{{cite news|last=Barron|first=James|title=Riding the Past From Grand Central|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 8, 1991|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/04/08/nyregion/riding-the-past-from-grand-central.html|accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nUnder the [[Penn Station Access]] project, [[Metro-North Railroad]] is studying ways it could also serve Penn Station. One alternative being studied would run some [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]] commuter trains into Penn Station via the Empire Connection, possibly with new station stops at West 125th and West 62nd Streets.\n\n== High Line park ==\n[[File:Highline NYC 3705376658 529a375621.jpg|thumb|A section of the High Line at Tenth Avenue and 17th Street]]\n{{Main|High Line}}\nIn the early 1980s, as the connections to Penn Station were created, the line south of 34th Street was disconnected from the rest of the [[National rail network|U.S. railway system]]. This portion of the line, entirely on an elevated viaduct, stood dormant for over thirty years. This viaduct, now called the High Line, has been turned into an elevated park which opened in phases from June 2009 to fall 2014.<ref name=\"marritz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wnyc.org/articles/wnyc-news/2011/jun/07/high-line/|last=Marritz|first=Ilya|title=As the High Line Grows, Business Falls in Love with a Public Park|publisher=[[WNYC]]|date=June 7, 2011|accessdate=June 8, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"browne\">{{Cite news\n|url=http://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/06/07/high-notes-new-art-on-the-high-line/|title=High Notes - New Art on the High Line|last=Browne|first=Alex|date=June 7, 2011|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"pesce\">{{Cite news\n|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/ny_local/2011/06/07/2011-06-07_hotly_anticipated_second_section_of_the_high_line_opens_adding_10_blocks_of_elev.html|title=Hotly anticipated second section of the High Line opens, adding 10 blocks of elevated park space|last=Pesce|first=Nicole Lyn|date=June 7, 2011|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303701304579550201916425732 | title=Artist's 'Ruins' Rise on the High Line - WSJ.com | work=[[Wall Street Journal]] | date=May 11, 2014 | accessdate=May 12, 2014 | last=Battaglia | first=Andy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehighline.org/about/high-line-at-the-rail-yards | title=High Line at the Rail Yards | work=Friends of the High Line | accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[East Side Access]], companion project to Penn Station Access\n* [[Freedom Tunnel]]\n\n==References==\n\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n*{{Cite journal|first=Theodore W.|last=Scull|title=Change at Penn Station: an opportunity|work=[[Trains (magazine)|Trains]]|date= August 1991}}\n*{{Cite journal|first=Bob|last=Johnston|title=New Amtrak cuts signal a long siege|work=[[Trains (magazine)|Trains]]|date=June 1995}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title|from=West Side Line (NYCRR)}}\n*[http://www.railroad.net/articles/railfanning/westside/ New York Central's 1934 West Side Improvement] (1934 pamphlet)\n*[http://www.columbia.edu/~brennan/abandoned/bronx.html Abandoned Stations - Bronx Railroad Stations] (includes the West Side Line in Manhattan)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:West Side Line (Nycrr)}}\n[[Category:New York Central Railroad lines]]\n[[Category:Rail infrastructure in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:West Side Line| ]]\n", "name_user": "Kyle5113", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEmpire Connection", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_Side_Line"}
{"title_page": "Qubad Talabani", "text_new": "{{void}}{{Infobox State Representative\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Qubad Talabani\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image =Qubad Talabani Photo.jpg\n| state_assembly = [[Kurdish National Assembly]]\n| term_start = June 2014 \n| term_end =\n| office = Deputy Prime Minister of Kurdistan Region Government\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|7|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Iraqi of Kurdish descent\n| party = [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]]\n| residence = [[Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n| alma_mater =\n| religion = \n| signature =\n| website = \n| footnotes =\n|father=[[Jalal Talabani]]\n|mother=Hero Ibrahim Ahmad\n}}\n\n'''Qubad Talabani''' (born 21 July 1977) is an Iraqi Kurdish politician who has been  the Deputy Prime Minister of the [[Kurdistan Region]] since 2014. Formerly serving as the representative of Kurdistan to the [[United States]], Qubad is the second son of Iraqi former President [[Jalal Talabani]].\n\n== Early life ==\nDeputy Prime Minister Talabani was born in 1977 and grew up in [[Surrey]], [[United Kingdom]] with his maternal grandparents, [[Ibrahim Ahmed]], a novelist, poet and a founder of the modern intellectual [[Kurdish People|Kurdish]] movement and Galawejh Ahmed (also a novelist). His family has been involved in Kurdish politics for decades; His father, [[Jalal Talabani]], was the President of the [[Republic of Iraq]] from 2006 until 2014. \n\nAfter graduating from High School, he obtained a Diploma in Motor Vehicle Engineering at [[Carshalton College]], and later received a degree in Mechanical Engineering at the [[Kingston University]] in London.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://gov.krd/english/government/deputy-prime-minister/|title=Qubad Talabani|website=Kurdistan Regional Government|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\nFrom 2001 to 2003, Qubad worked as a special assistant to  [[Barham Salih]], at that time the Representative of the [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]] (one of Iraq's leading Kurdish political parties) in Washington D.C., and later as the Deputy PUK Representative.<ref name=huff/> In 2003, he returned to [[Kurdistan]] for one year and served as the [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan|PUK]]'s Senior Foreign Relations officer to the coalition forces and the Coalition Provisional Authority. He also acted as a liaison officer between the PUK and U.S. military forces in [[Iraq]].<ref>[http://www.jmu.edu/jmuweb/general/news/general6403.shtml IRAQI PRESIDENT'S SON TO SPEAK ON IRAQ'S FUTURE]</ref> He was a leading negotiator in the drafting of the Transitional Administrative Law (TAL), the first Iraqi constitution since the overthrow of [[Saddam Hussein]].<ref name=huff>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/qubad-j-talabani ''The Huffington Post'']</ref>\n\nIn April 2004, Qubad returned to the US, and was stationed as the Representative of the PUK and Kurdistan.\n\nIn 2006, with the unification of the two administrations in [[Kurdistan]] and following the forming of the [[Democratic Patriotic Alliance of Kurdistan]] and the establishment of the [[Kurdish National Assembly]],<ref>[http://www2.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2007/0706.rozen.html The Scion Kurdistan's man in Washington By Laura Rozen]</ref> Qubad was appointed as the first representative of the Kurdistan Region, a position he has held until 2012<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2014 he was nominated Deputy Prime Minister of the Government of the Kurdistan region and was involved in the implementation of the biometric registration system for government employees.<ref name=\":0\" />  \n\nHe was first sworn in as Deputy Prime Minister of the KRG Cabinet<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://president.gov.krd/en/nechirvan-barzani-praises-the-eighth-government-cabinet/|title=Nechirvan Barzani Commends the 8th Cabinet of the Kurdistan Regional Government|date=2019-07-06|website=President of the Kurdistan Region of Iraq|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> in June 2014, where he took office. Receiving no fiscal transfers from the [[Government of Iraq]] (GoI), coupled with rapidly declining oil prices, the Kurdistan region was in the midst of a severe financial crisis<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/a38b70a2-e39c-45d4-94e6-d5f3a3eef2ab/KRG-alone-in-solving-financial-crisis|title=KRG alone in solving financial crisis|last=Kurdistan24|website=Kurdistan24|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>. Moreover, the [[Islamic State of Iraq|Islamic State]] was rampaging its way throughout Iraq, claiming territory and establishing itself as one of history\u2019s most brutal terrorist organizations, resulting in a major humanitarian crisis that forced 1.8 million people to flee war and violence and seek refuge in the Kurdistan region<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/06/iraqis-seek-refuge-kurdish-north-20146217557290137.html Iraqis seeks refuge in Kurdish north]</ref>. During this period, the KRG successfully oversaw a package of reforms. \n\nA major part of the KRG\u2019s economic reform plan included improving oversight of government expenditures. To that end, Talabani successfully oversaw the design and implementation of his government\u2019s biometric registration program.<ref name=\":0\" />  \n\nDuring the KRG\u2019s Seventh Cabinet, Talabani established and headed up the Department of Coordination and Follow-up to facilitate inter-ministerial coordination. He directed that KRG agency on behalf of the Prime Minister for two years.\n\nIn the parliamentary elections of the Kurdistan region of 2018<ref name=\":0\" /> he was elected to parliament but he did not assume his post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/54d4104c-931e-42f4-88a6-c0ded133c936|title=Qubad Talabani, two other MPs relinquish seats in Kurdistan parliament|last=Kurdistan24|website=Kurdistan24|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>    \n\nQubad Talabani appears frequently on major television networks and in the press where he discusses Iraqi and Kurdistan issues.<ref name=huff/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDeputy Prime Minister Talabani is the son of [[Jalal Talabani]] and [[Hero Ibrahim Ahmed]] and the younger brother of PUK political figure [[Bafel Talabani]]. He lives in [[Erbil]] with his wife [[Sherri Kraham]] whom he married in Il Castello del Palagio in Italy in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080212094457/http://www.chianticlassico.com/english/magazine/200505/articolo0.asp|title=DIPLOMATIC WEDDING IN CHIANTI - Chianti Classico Magazine|date=2008-02-12|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> and their two children, Ari and Lara. \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160204145003/http://qubadsblog.com/ Qubad Talabani's blog]\n* [http://www.sourcewatch.org/index.php?title=Qubad_Talabani Profile] at [[SourceWatch]]\n*{{C-SPAN|Qubad Talabani}}\n* [[List of presidents of Iraq]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Talabani, Qubad}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Kingston University]]\n[[Category:Patriotic Union of Kurdistan politicians]]\n[[Category:Children of national leaders]]\n[[Category:Kurdish politicians]]\n[[Category:Government of Kurdistan Region]]\n", "text_old": "{{void}}{{Infobox State Representative\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Qubad Talabani\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image =Qubad Talabani Photo.jpg\n| state_assembly = [[Kurdish National Assembly]]\n| term_start = June 2014 \n| term_end =\n| office = Deputy Prime Minister of Kurdistan Region Government\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|7|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Iraqi of Kurdish descent\n| party = [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]]\n| residence = [[Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n| alma_mater =\n| religion = \n| signature =\n| website = \n| footnotes =\n|father=[[Jalal Talabani]]\n|mother=Hero Ibrahim Ahmad\n}}\n\n'''Qubad Talabani''' (born 21 July 1977) is an Iraqi Kurdish politician who has been  the Deputy Prime Minister of the [[Kurdistan Region]] since 2014. Formerly serving as the representative of Kurdistan to the [[United States]], Qubad is the second son of Iraqi former President [[Jalal Talabani]].\n\n== Early life ==\nDeputy Prime Minister Talabani was born in 1977 and grew up in [[Surrey]], [[United Kingdom]] with his maternal grandparents, [[Ibrahim Ahmed]], a novelist, poet and a founder of the modern intellectual [[Kurdish People|Kurdish]] movement and Galawejh Ahmed (also a novelist). His family has been involved in Kurdish politics for decades; His father, [[Jalal Talabani]], was the President of the [[Republic of Iraq]] from 2006 until 2014. \n\nAfter graduating from High School, he obtained a Diploma in Motor Vehicle Engineering at [[Carshalton College]], and later received a degree in Mechanical Engineering at the [[Kingston University]] in London.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://gov.krd/english/government/deputy-prime-minister/|title=Qubad Talabani|website=Kurdistan Regional Government|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\nFrom 2001 to 2003, Qubad worked as a special assistant to  [[Barham Salih]], at that time the Representative of the [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]] (one of Iraq's leading Kurdish political parties) in Washington D.C., and later as the Deputy PUK Representative.<ref name=huff/> In 2003, he returned to [[Kurdistan]] for one year and served as the [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan|PUK]]'s Senior Foreign Relations officer to the coalition forces and the Coalition Provisional Authority. He also acted as a liaison officer between the PUK and U.S. military forces in [[Iraq]].<ref>[http://www.jmu.edu/jmuweb/general/news/general6403.shtml IRAQI PRESIDENT'S SON TO SPEAK ON IRAQ'S FUTURE]</ref> He was a leading negotiator in the drafting of the Transitional Administrative Law (TAL), the first Iraqi constitution since the overthrow of [[Saddam Hussein]].<ref name=huff>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/qubad-j-talabani ''The Huffington Post'']</ref>\n\nIn April 2004, Qubad returned to the US, and was stationed as the Representative of the PUK and Kurdistan.\n\nIn 2006, with the unification of the two administrations in [[Kurdistan]] and following the forming of the [[Democratic Patriotic Alliance of Kurdistan]] and the establishment of the [[Kurdish National Assembly]],<ref>[http://www2.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2007/0706.rozen.html The Scion Kurdistan's man in Washington By Laura Rozen]</ref> Qubad was appointed as the first representative of the Kurdistan Region, a position he has held until 2012<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2014 he was nominated Deputy Prime Minister of the Government of the Kurdistan region and was involved in the implementation of the biometric registration system for government employees.<ref name=\":0\" />  \n\nHe was first sworn in as Deputy Prime Minister of the KRG Cabinet<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://president.gov.krd/en/nechirvan-barzani-praises-the-eighth-government-cabinet/|title=Nechirvan Barzani Commends the 8th Cabinet of the Kurdistan Regional Government|date=2019-07-06|website=President of the Kurdistan Region of Iraq|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> in June 2014, where he took office. Receiving no fiscal transfers from the [[Government of Iraq]] (GoI), coupled with rapidly declining oil prices, the Kurdistan region was in the midst of a severe financial crisis<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/a38b70a2-e39c-45d4-94e6-d5f3a3eef2ab/KRG-alone-in-solving-financial-crisis|title=KRG alone in solving financial crisis|last=Kurdistan24|website=Kurdistan24|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>. Moreover, the [[Islamic State of Iraq|Islamic State]] was rampaging its way throughout Iraq, claiming territory and establishing itself as one of history\u2019s most brutal terrorist organizations, resulting in a major humanitarian crisis that forced 1.8 million people to flee war and violence and seek refuge in the Kurdistan region<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/06/iraqis-seek-refuge-kurdish-north-20146217557290137.html Iraqis seeks refuge in Kurdish north]</ref>. During this period, the KRG successfully oversaw a package of reforms. \n\nA major part of the KRG\u2019s economic reform plan included improving oversight of government expenditures. To that end, Talabani successfully oversaw the design and implementation of his government\u2019s biometric registration program.<ref name=\":0\" />  \n\nDuring the KRG\u2019s Seventh Cabinet, Talabani established and headed up the Department of Coordination and Follow-up to facilitate inter-ministerial coordination. He directed that KRG agency on behalf of the Prime Minister for two years.\n\nIn the parliamentary elections of the Kurdistan region of 2018<ref name=\":0\" /> he was elected to parliament but he did not assume his post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/54d4104c-931e-42f4-88a6-c0ded133c936|title=Qubad Talabani, two other MPs relinquish seats in Kurdistan parliament|last=Kurdistan24|website=Kurdistan24|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>    \n\nQubad Talabani appears frequently on major television networks and in the press where he discusses Iraqi and Kurdistan issues.<ref name=huff/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDeputy Prime Minister Talabani is the son of [[Jalal Talabani]] and [[Hero Ibrahim Ahmed]] and the younger brother of PUK political figure [[Bafel Talabani]]. He lives in [[Erbil]] with his wife [[Sherri Kraham]] whom he married in Il Castello del Palagio in Italy in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080212094457/http://www.chianticlassico.com/english/magazine/200505/articolo0.asp|title=DIPLOMATIC WEDDING IN CHIANTI - Chianti Classico Magazine|date=2008-02-12|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> and their two children, Ari and Lara. \n\n== References ==